# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atomic-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms are extremely small, typically around 100 picometers across.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A human hair is about a million carbon atoms wide.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms are smaller than the shortest wavelength of visible light, which means humans cannot see atoms with conventional microscopes.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] They are so small that accurately predicting their behavior using classical physics is not possible due to quantum effects.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] More than 99.94% of an atom's mass is in the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Protons have a positive electric charge and neutrons have no charge, so the nucleus is positively charged.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electrons are negatively charged, and this opposing charge is what binds them to the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If the numbers of protons and electrons are equal, as they normally are, then the atom is electrically neutral as a whole.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If an atom has more electrons than protons, then it has an overall negative charge and is called a negative ion (or anion).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Conversely, if it has more protons than electrons, it has a positive charge and is called a positive ion (or cation).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electrons of an atom are attracted to the protons in an atomic nucleus by the electromagnetic force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The protons and neutrons in the nucleus are attracted to each other by the nuclear force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This force is usually stronger than the electromagnetic force that repels the positively charged protons from one another.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Under certain circumstances, the repelling electromagnetic force becomes stronger than the nuclear force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In this case, the nucleus splits and leaves behind different elements.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms can attach to one or more other atoms by chemical bonds to form chemical compounds such as molecules or crystals.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The ability of atoms to attach and detach from each other is responsible for most of the physical changes observed in nature.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Chemistry is the science that studies these changes.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The word *atom* is derived from the ancient Greek word *Atomos*, which means "uncuttable".
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] However, this ancient idea was based in philosophical reasoning rather than scientific reasoning.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Modern atomic theory is not based on these old concepts.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In the early 19th century, the scientist John Dalton found evidence that matter really is composed of discrete units, and so applied the word *atom* to those units.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The basic idea that matter is made up of tiny indivisible particles is an old idea that appeared in many ancient cultures.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These ancient ideas were based on philosophical reasoning rather than scientific evidence, and modern atomic theory is not based on these old concepts.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] That said, the word *atom* is derived from the term used by some ancient Greek philosophers, *atomos* ("uncuttable").
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In the early 1800s, John Dalton compiled experimental data gathered by him and other scientists and discovered a pattern now known as the "law of multiple proportions".
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] He noticed that in any group of chemical compounds which all contain two particular chemical elements, the amount of Element A per measure of Element B will differ across these compounds by ratios of small whole numbers.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This pattern suggested that each element combines with other elements in multiples of a basic unit of weight, with each element having a unit of unique weight.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Dalton decided to call these units "atoms".
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For example, there are two types of tin oxide: one is a grey powder that is 88.1% tin and 11.9% oxygen, and the other is a white powder that is 78.7% tin and 21.3% oxygen.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Adjusting these figures, in the grey powder there is about 13.5 g of oxygen for every 100 g of tin, and in the white powder there is about 27 g of oxygen for every 100 g of tin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Dalton concluded that in the grey oxide there is one atom of oxygen for every atom of tin, and in the white oxide there are two atoms of oxygen for every atom of tin (SnO and SnO2).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] There is one type of iron oxide that is a black powder which is 78.1% iron and 21.9% oxygen; and there is another iron oxide that is a red powder which is 70.4% iron and 29.6% oxygen.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Adjusting these figures, in the black powder there is about 28 g of oxygen for every 100 g of iron, and in the red powder there is about 42 g of oxygen for every 100 g of iron.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Dalton concluded that in these oxides, for every two atoms of iron, there are two or three atoms of oxygen respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These substances are known today as iron(II) oxide and iron(III) oxide, and their formulas are FeO and Fe2O3 respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Iron(II) oxide's formula is normally written as FeO, but since it is a crystalline substance we could alternately write it as Fe2O2, and when we contrast that with Fe2O3, the 2:3 ratio for the oxygen is plain to see.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] As a final example: nitrous oxide is 63.3% nitrogen and 36.7% oxygen, nitric oxide is 44.05% nitrogen and 55.95% oxygen, and nitrogen dioxide is 29.5% nitrogen and 70.5% oxygen.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Adjusting these figures, in nitrous oxide there is 80 g of oxygen for every 140 g of nitrogen, in nitric oxide there is about 160 g of oxygen for every 140 g of nitrogen, and in nitrogen dioxide there is 320 g of oxygen for every 140 g of nitrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The respective formulas for these oxides are N2O, NO, and NO2.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson discovered that cathode rays can be deflected by electric and magnetic fields, which meant that cathode rays are not a form of light but made of electrically charged particles, and their charge was negative given the direction the particles were deflected in.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] He measured these particles to be 1,700 times lighter than hydrogen (the lightest atom).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] He called these new particles *corpuscles* but they were later renamed *electrons* since these are the particles that carry electricity.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson also showed that electrons were identical to particles given off by photoelectric and radioactive materials.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson explained that an electric current is the passing of electrons from one atom to the next, and when there was no current the electrons embedded themselves in the atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This in turn meant that atoms were not indivisible as scientists thought.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The atom was composed of electrons whose negative charge was balanced out by some source of positive charge to create an electrically neutral atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Ions, Thomson explained, must be atoms which have an excess or shortage of electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electrons in the atom logically had to be balanced out by a commensurate amount of positive charge, but Thomson had no idea where this positive charge came from, so he tentatively proposed that it was everywhere in the atom, the atom being in the shape of a sphere.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This was the mathematically simplest hypothesis to fit the available evidence, or lack thereof.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Following from this, Thomson imagined that the balance of electrostatic forces would distribute the electrons throughout the sphere in a more or less even manner.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson's model is popularly known as the plum pudding model, though neither Thomson nor his colleagues used this analogy.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson's model was incomplete, it was unable to predict any other properties of the elements such as emission spectra and valencies.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] It was soon rendered obsolete by the discovery of the atomic nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Between 1908 and 1913, Ernest Rutherford and his colleagues Hans Geiger and Ernest Marsden performed a series of experiments in which they bombarded thin foils of metal with a beam of alpha particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] They did this to measure the scattering patterns of the alpha particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] They spotted a small number of alpha particles being deflected by angles greater than 90°.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This shouldn't have been possible according to the Thomson model of the atom, whose charges were too diffuse to produce a sufficiently strong electric field.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The deflections should have all been negligible.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Rutherford proposed that the positive charge of the atom is concentrated in a tiny volume at the center of the atom and that the electrons surround this nucleus in a diffuse cloud.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This nucleus carried almost all of the atom's mass.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Only such an intense concentration of charge, anchored by its high mass, could produce an electric field that could deflect the alpha particles so strongly.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A problem in classical mechanics is that an accelerating charged particle radiates electromagnetic radiation, causing the particle to lose kinetic energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Circular motion counts as acceleration, which means that an electron orbiting a central charge should spiral down into that nucleus as it loses speed.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In 1913, the physicist Niels Bohr proposed a new model in which the electrons of an atom were assumed to orbit the nucleus but could only do so in a finite set of orbits, and could jump between these orbits only in discrete changes of energy corresponding to absorption or radiation of a photon.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This quantization was used to explain why the electrons' orbits are stable and why elements absorb and emit electromagnetic radiation in discrete spectra.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Bohr's model could only predict the emission spectra of hydrogen, not atoms with more than one electron.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Back in 1815, William Prout observed that the atomic weights of many elements were multiples of hydrogen's atomic weight, which is in fact true for all of them if one takes isotopes into account.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson found that the positive charge of a hydrogen ion is equal to the negative charge of an electron, and these were then the smallest known charged particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson later found that the positive charge in an atom is a positive multiple of an electron's negative charge.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In 1913, Henry Moseley discovered that the frequencies of X-ray emissions from an excited atom were a mathematical function of its atomic number and hydrogen's nuclear charge.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In 1919, Rutherford bombarded nitrogen gas with alpha particles and detected hydrogen ions being emitted from the gas, and concluded that they were produced by alpha particles hitting and splitting the nuclei of the nitrogen atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These observations led Rutherford to conclude that the hydrogen nucleus is a singular particle with a positive charge equal to the electron's negative charge.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] He named this particle "proton" in 1920.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The number of protons in an atom (which Rutherford called the "atomic number") was found to be equal to the element's ordinal number on the periodic table and therefore provided a simple and clear-cut way of distinguishing the elements from each other.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The atomic weight of each element is higher than its proton number, so Rutherford hypothesized that the surplus weight was carried by unknown particles with no electric charge and a mass equal to that of the proton.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In 1928, Walter Bothe observed that beryllium emitted a highly penetrating, electrically neutral radiation when bombarded with alpha particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] It was later discovered that this radiation could knock hydrogen atoms out of paraffin wax.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Chadwick now claimed these particles as Rutherford's neutrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In 1925, Werner Heisenberg published the first consistent mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics (matrix mechanics).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] One year earlier, Louis de Broglie had proposed that all particles behave like waves to some extent, and in 1926 Erwin Schrödinger used this idea to develop the Schrödinger equation, which describes electrons as three-dimensional waveforms rather than points in space.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A consequence of using waveforms to describe particles is that it is mathematically impossible to obtain precise values for both the position and momentum of a particle at a given point in time.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This became known as the uncertainty principle, formulated by Werner Heisenberg in 1927.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In this concept, for a given accuracy in measuring a position one could only obtain a range of probable values for momentum, and vice versa.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thus, the planetary model of the atom was discarded in favor of one that described atomic orbital zones around the nucleus where a given electron is most likely to be found.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This model was able to explain observations of atomic behavior that previous models could not, such as certain structural and spectral patterns of atoms larger than hydrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Though the word *atom* originally denoted a particle that cannot be cut into smaller particles, in modern scientific usage the atom is composed of various subatomic particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The constituent particles of an atom are the electron, the proton, and the neutron.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electron is the least massive of these particles by four orders of magnitude at 9.11×10−31 kg, with a negative electrical charge and a size that is too small to be measured using available techniques.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] It was the lightest particle with a positive rest mass measured, until the discovery of neutrino mass.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Under ordinary conditions, electrons are bound to the positively charged nucleus by the attraction created from opposite electric charges.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Electrons have been known since the late 19th century, mostly thanks to J.J.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thomson; see history of subatomic physics for details.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Protons have a positive charge and a mass of 1.6726×10−27 kg.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The number of protons in an atom is called its atomic number.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Ernest Rutherford (1919) observed that nitrogen under alpha-particle bombardment ejects what appeared to be hydrogen nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] By 1920, he had accepted that the hydrogen nucleus is a distinct particle within the atom and named it proton.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Neutrons have no electrical charge and have a mass of 1.6749×10−27 kg.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Neutrons are the heaviest of the three constituent particles, but their mass can be reduced by the nuclear binding energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Neutrons and protons (collectively known as nucleons) have comparable dimensions—on the order of 2.5×10−15 m—although the 'surface' of these particles is not sharply defined.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The neutron was discovered in 1932 by the English physicist James Chadwick.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In the Standard Model of physics, electrons are truly elementary particles with no internal structure, whereas protons and neutrons are composite particles composed of elementary particles called quarks.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] There are two types of quarks in atoms, each having a fractional electric charge.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Protons are composed of two up quarks (each with charge +⁠2/3⁠) and one down quark (with a charge of −⁠1/3⁠).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Neutrons consist of one up quark and two down quarks.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This distinction accounts for the difference in mass and charge between the two particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The quarks are held together by the strong interaction (or strong force), which is mediated by gluons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The protons and neutrons, in turn, are held to each other in the nucleus by the nuclear force, which is a residuum of the strong force that has somewhat different range-properties (see the article on the nuclear force for more).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The gluon is a member of the family of gauge bosons, which are elementary particles that mediate physical forces.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] All the bound protons and neutrons in an atom make up a tiny atomic nucleus, and are collectively called nucleons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The radius of a nucleus is approximately equal to $1.07{\sqrt[{3}]{A}}$ femtometres, where A is the total number of nucleons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This is much smaller than the radius of the atom, which is on the order of 105 fm.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The nucleons are bound together by a short-ranged attractive potential called the residual strong force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] At distances smaller than 2.5 fm this force is much more powerful than the electrostatic force that causes positively charged protons to repel each other.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms of the same element have the same number of protons, called the atomic number.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Within a single element, the number of neutrons may vary, determining the isotope of that element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The total number of protons and neutrons determine the nuclide.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The number of neutrons relative to the protons determines the stability of the nucleus, with certain isotopes undergoing radioactive decay.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The proton, the electron, and the neutron are classified as fermions.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Fermions obey the Pauli exclusion principle which prohibits *identical* fermions, such as multiple protons, from occupying the same quantum state at the same time.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thus, every proton in the nucleus must occupy a quantum state different from all other protons, and the same applies to all neutrons of the nucleus and to all electrons of the electron cloud.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A nucleus that has a different number of protons than neutrons can potentially drop to a lower energy state through a radioactive decay that causes the number of protons and neutrons to more closely match.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] As a result, atoms with matching numbers of protons and neutrons are more stable against decay, but with increasing atomic number, the mutual repulsion of the protons requires an increasing proportion of neutrons to maintain the stability of the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The number of protons and neutrons in the atomic nucleus can be modified, although this can require very high energies because of the strong force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Nuclear fusion occurs when multiple atomic particles join to form a heavier nucleus, such as through the energetic collision of two nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For example, at the core of the Sun protons require energies of 3 to 10 keV to overcome their mutual repulsion—the coulomb barrier—and fuse together into a single nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Nuclear fission is the opposite process, causing a nucleus to split into two smaller nuclei—usually through radioactive decay.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The nucleus can also be modified through bombardment by high energy subatomic particles or photons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If this modifies the number of protons in a nucleus, the atom changes to a different chemical element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This deficit is part of the binding energy of the new nucleus, and it is the non-recoverable loss of the energy that causes the fused particles to remain together in a state that requires this energy to separate.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The fusion of two nuclei that create larger nuclei with lower atomic numbers than iron and nickel—a total nucleon number of about 60—is usually an exothermic process that releases more energy than is required to bring them together.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] It is this energy-releasing process that makes nuclear fusion in stars a self-sustaining reaction.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For heavier nuclei, the binding energy per nucleon begins to decrease.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] That means that a fusion process producing a nucleus that has an atomic number higher than about 26, and a mass number higher than about 60, is an endothermic process.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thus, more massive nuclei cannot undergo an energy-producing fusion reaction that can sustain the hydrostatic equilibrium of a star.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electrons in an atom are attracted to the protons in the nucleus by the electromagnetic force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This force binds the electrons inside an electrostatic potential well surrounding the smaller nucleus, which means that an external source of energy is needed for the electron to escape.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The closer an electron is to the nucleus, the greater the attractive force.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Hence electrons bound near the center of the potential well require more energy to escape than those at greater separations.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Electrons, like other particles, have properties of both a particle and a wave.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electron cloud is a region inside the potential well where each electron forms a type of three-dimensional standing wave—a wave form that does not move relative to the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This behavior is defined by an atomic orbital, a mathematical function that characterises the probability that an electron appears to be at a particular location when its position is measured.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Only a discrete (or quantized) set of these orbitals exist around the nucleus, as other possible wave patterns rapidly decay into a more stable form.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Orbitals can have one or more ring or node structures, and differ from each other in size, shape and orientation.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Each atomic orbital corresponds to a particular energy level of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electron can change its state to a higher energy level by absorbing a photon with sufficient energy to boost it into the new quantum state.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Likewise, through spontaneous emission, an electron in a higher energy state can drop to a lower energy state while radiating the excess energy as a photon.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These characteristic energy values, defined by the differences in the energies of the quantum states, are responsible for atomic spectral lines.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The amount of energy needed to remove or add an electron—the electron binding energy—is far less than the binding energy of nucleons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For example, it requires only 13.6 eV to strip a ground-state electron from a hydrogen atom, compared to 2.23 *million* eV for splitting a deuterium nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms are electrically neutral if they have an equal number of protons and electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms that have either a deficit or a surplus of electrons are called ions.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Electrons that are farthest from the nucleus may be transferred to other nearby atoms or shared between atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] By this mechanism, atoms are able to bond into molecules and other types of chemical compounds like ionic and covalent network crystals.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] By definition, any two atoms with an identical number of *protons* in their nuclei belong to the same chemical element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms with equal numbers of protons but a different number of *neutrons* are different isotopes of the same element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For example, all hydrogen atoms admit exactly one proton, but isotopes exist with no neutrons (hydrogen-1, by far the most common form, also called protium), one neutron (deuterium), two neutrons (tritium) and more than two neutrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The known elements form a set of atomic numbers, from the single-proton element hydrogen up to the 118-proton element oganesson.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] All known isotopes of elements with atomic numbers greater than 82 are radioactive, although the radioactivity of element 83 (bismuth) is so slight as to be practically negligible.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] About 339 nuclides occur naturally on Earth, of which 251 (about 74%) have not been observed to decay, and are referred to as "stable isotopes".
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Only 90 nuclides are stable theoretically, while another 161 (bringing the total to 251) have not been observed to decay, even though in theory it is energetically possible.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These are also formally classified as "stable".
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] An additional 35 radioactive nuclides have half-lives longer than 100 million years, and are long-lived enough to have been present since the birth of the Solar System.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This collection of 286 nuclides are known as primordial nuclides.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Finally, an additional 53 short-lived nuclides are known to occur naturally, as daughter products of primordial nuclide decay (such as radium from uranium), or as products of natural energetic processes on Earth, such as cosmic ray bombardment (for example, carbon-14).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For 80 of the chemical elements, at least one stable isotope exists.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] As a rule, there is only a handful of stable isotopes for each of these elements, the average being 3.1 stable isotopes per element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Twenty-six "monoisotopic elements" have only a single stable isotope, while the largest number of stable isotopes observed for any element is ten, for the element tin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Elements 43, 61, and all elements numbered 83 or higher have no stable isotopes.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Stability of isotopes is affected by the ratio of protons to neutrons, and also by the presence of certain "magic numbers" of neutrons or protons that represent closed and filled quantum shells.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These quantum shells correspond to a set of energy levels within the shell model of the nucleus; filled shells, such as the filled shell of 50 protons for tin, confers unusual stability on the nuclide.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Of the 251 known stable nuclides, only four have both an odd number of protons *and* odd number of neutrons: hydrogen-2 (deuterium), lithium-6, boron-10, and nitrogen-14.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] (Tantalum-180m is odd-odd and observationally stable, but is predicted to decay with a very long half-life.) Also, only four naturally occurring, radioactive odd-odd nuclides have a half-life over a billion years: potassium-40, vanadium-50, lanthanum-138, and lutetium-176.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Most odd-odd nuclei are highly unstable with respect to beta decay, because the decay products are even-even, and are therefore more strongly bound, due to nuclear pairing effects.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The large majority of an atom's mass comes from the protons and neutrons that make it up.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The total number of these particles (called "nucleons") in a given atom is called the mass number.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] It is a positive integer and dimensionless (instead of having dimension of mass), because it expresses a count.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] An example of use of a mass number is "carbon-12," which has 12 nucleons (six protons and six neutrons).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The actual mass of an atom at rest is often expressed in daltons (Da), also called the unified atomic mass unit (u).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This unit is defined as a twelfth of the mass of a free neutral atom of carbon-12, which is approximately 1.66×10−27 kg.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Hydrogen-1 (the lightest isotope of hydrogen which is also the nuclide with the lowest mass) has an atomic weight of 1.007825 Da.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The value of this number is called the atomic mass.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A given atom has an atomic mass approximately equal (within 1%) to its mass number times the dalton (for example the mass of a nitrogen-14 is roughly 14 Da), but this number will not be exactly an integer except (by definition) in the case of carbon-12.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The heaviest stable atom is lead-208, with a mass of 207.9766521 Da.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] As even the most massive atoms are far too light to work with directly, chemists instead use the unit of moles.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] One mole of atoms of any element always has the same number of atoms (about 6.022×1023).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This number was chosen so that if an element has an atomic mass of 1 u, a mole of atoms of that element has a mass close to one gram.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Because of the definition of the dalton, each carbon-12 atom has an atomic mass of exactly 12 Da, and so a mole of carbon-12 atoms weighs exactly 0.012 kg.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms lack a well-defined outer boundary, so their dimensions are usually described in terms of an atomic radius.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This is a measure of the distance out to which the electron cloud extends from the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This assumes the atom to exhibit a spherical shape, which is only obeyed for atoms in vacuum or free space.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atomic radii may be derived from the distances between two nuclei when the two atoms are joined in a chemical bond.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The radius varies with the location of an atom on the atomic chart, the type of chemical bond, the number of neighboring atoms (coordination number) and a quantum mechanical property known as spin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] On the periodic table of the elements, atom size tends to increase when moving down columns, but decrease when moving across rows (left to right).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Consequently, the smallest atom is helium with a radius of 32 pm, while one of the largest is caesium at 225 pm.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] When subjected to external forces, like electrical fields, the shape of an atom may deviate from spherical symmetry.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The deformation depends on the field magnitude and the orbital type of outer shell electrons, as shown by group-theoretical considerations.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Aspherical deviations might be elicited for instance in crystals, where large crystal-electrical fields may occur at low-symmetry lattice sites.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Significant ellipsoidal deformations have been shown to occur for sulfur ions and chalcogen ions in pyrite-type compounds.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atomic dimensions are thousands of times smaller than the wavelengths of light (400–700 nm) so they cannot be viewed using an optical microscope, although individual atoms can be observed using a scanning tunneling microscope.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] To visualize the minuteness of the atom, consider that a typical human hair is about 1 million carbon atoms in width.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A single drop of water contains about 2 sextillion (2×1021) atoms of oxygen, and twice the number of hydrogen atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A single carat diamond with a mass of 2×10−4 kg contains about 10 sextillion (1022) atoms of carbon.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If an apple were magnified to the size of the Earth, then the atoms in the apple would be approximately the size of the original apple.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Every element has one or more isotopes that have unstable nuclei that are subject to radioactive decay, causing the nucleus to emit particles or electromagnetic radiation.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Radioactivity can occur when the radius of a nucleus is large compared with the radius of the strong force, which only acts over distances on the order of 1 fm.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Other more rare types of radioactive decay include ejection of neutrons or protons or clusters of nucleons from a nucleus, or more than one beta particle.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] An analog of gamma emission which allows excited nuclei to lose energy in a different way, is internal conversion—a process that produces high-speed electrons that are not beta rays, followed by production of high-energy photons that are not gamma rays.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] A few large nuclei explode into two or more charged fragments of varying masses plus several neutrons, in a decay called spontaneous nuclear fission.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Each radioactive isotope has a characteristic decay time period—the half-life—that is determined by the amount of time needed for half of a sample to decay.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This is an exponential decay process that steadily decreases the proportion of the remaining isotope by 50% every half-life.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Hence after two half-lives have passed only 25% of the isotope is present, and so forth.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Elementary particles possess an intrinsic quantum mechanical property known as spin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This is analogous to the angular momentum of an object that is spinning around its center of mass, although strictly speaking these particles are believed to be point-like and cannot be said to be rotating.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Spin is measured in units of the reduced Planck constant (ħ), with electrons, protons and neutrons all having spin 1⁄2 ħ, or "spin-1⁄2".
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In an atom, electrons in motion around the nucleus possess orbital angular momentum in addition to their spin, while the nucleus itself possesses angular momentum due to its nuclear spin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The magnetic field produced by an atom—its magnetic moment—is determined by these various forms of angular momentum, just as a rotating charged object classically produces a magnetic field, but the most dominant contribution comes from electron spin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Due to the nature of electrons to obey the Pauli exclusion principle, in which no two electrons may be found in the same quantum state, bound electrons pair up with each other, with one member of each pair in a spin up state and the other in the opposite, spin down state.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thus these spins cancel each other out, reducing the total magnetic dipole moment to zero in some atoms with even number of electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In ferromagnetic elements such as iron, cobalt and nickel, an odd number of electrons leads to an unpaired electron and a net overall magnetic moment.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The orbitals of neighboring atoms overlap and a lower energy state is achieved when the spins of unpaired electrons are aligned with each other, a spontaneous process known as an exchange interaction.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] When the magnetic moments of ferromagnetic atoms are lined up, the material can produce a measurable macroscopic field.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Paramagnetic materials have atoms with magnetic moments that line up in random directions when no magnetic field is present, but the magnetic moments of the individual atoms line up in the presence of a field.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The nucleus of an atom will have no spin when it has even numbers of both neutrons and protons, but for other cases of odd numbers, the nucleus may have a spin.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Normally nuclei with spin are aligned in random directions because of thermal equilibrium, but for certain elements (such as xenon-129) it is possible to polarize a significant proportion of the nuclear spin states so that they are aligned in the same direction—a condition called hyperpolarization.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This has important applications in magnetic resonance imaging.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The potential energy of an electron in an atom is negative relative to when the distance from the nucleus goes to infinity; its dependence on the electron's position reaches the minimum inside the nucleus, roughly in inverse proportion to the distance.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] In the quantum-mechanical model, a bound electron can occupy only a set of states centered on the nucleus, and each state corresponds to a specific energy level; see time-independent Schrödinger equation for a theoretical explanation.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] An energy level can be measured by the amount of energy needed to unbind the electron from the atom, and is usually given in units of electronvolts (eV).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The lowest energy state of a bound electron is called the ground state, i.e., stationary state, while an electron transition to a higher level results in an excited state.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The electron's energy increases along with *n* because the (average) distance to the nucleus increases.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Dependence of the energy on ℓ is caused not by the electrostatic potential of the nucleus, but by interaction between electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Electrons jump between orbitals in a particle-like fashion.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For example, if a single photon strikes the electrons, only a single electron changes states in response to the photon; see Electron properties.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The energy of an emitted photon is proportional to its frequency, so these specific energy levels appear as distinct bands in the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Each element has a characteristic spectrum that can depend on the nuclear charge, subshells filled by electrons, the electromagnetic interactions between the electrons and other factors.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] When a continuous spectrum of energy is passed through a gas or plasma, some of the photons are absorbed by atoms, causing electrons to change their energy level.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Those excited electrons that remain bound to their atom spontaneously emit this energy as a photon, traveling in a random direction, and so drop back to lower energy levels.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thus the atoms behave like a filter that forms a series of dark absorption bands in the energy output.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] An observer viewing the atoms from a view that does not include the continuous spectrum in the background, instead sees a series of emission lines from the photons emitted by the atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Spectroscopic measurements of the strength and width of atomic spectral lines allow the composition and physical properties of a substance to be determined.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Close examination of the spectral lines reveals that some display a fine structure splitting.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This occurs because of spin–orbit coupling, which is an interaction between the spin and motion of the outermost electron.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] When an atom is in an external magnetic field, spectral lines become split into three or more components; a phenomenon called the Zeeman effect.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This is caused by the interaction of the magnetic field with the magnetic moment of the atom and its electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Some atoms can have multiple electron configurations with the same energy level, which thus appear as a single spectral line.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The interaction of the magnetic field with the atom shifts these electron configurations to slightly different energy levels, resulting in multiple spectral lines.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The presence of an external electric field can cause a comparable splitting and shifting of spectral lines by modifying the electron energy levels, a phenomenon called the Stark effect.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If a bound electron is in an excited state, an interacting photon with the proper energy can cause stimulated emission of a photon with a matching energy level.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For this to occur, the electron must drop to a lower energy state that has an energy difference matching the energy of the interacting photon.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The emitted photon and the interacting photon then move off in parallel and with matching phases.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] That is, the wave patterns of the two photons are synchronized.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This physical property is used to make lasers, which can emit a coherent beam of light energy in a narrow frequency band.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Valency is the combining power of an element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] It is determined by the number of bonds it can form to other atoms or groups.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The outermost electron shell of an atom in its uncombined state is known as the valence shell, and the electrons in that shell are called valence electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The number of valence electrons determines the bonding behavior with other atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms tend to chemically react with each other in a manner that fills (or empties) their outer valence shells.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For example, a transfer of a single electron between atoms is a useful approximation for bonds that form between atoms with one-electron more than a filled shell, and others that are one-electron short of a full shell, such as occurs in the compound sodium chloride and other chemical ionic salts.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Many elements display multiple valences, or tendencies to share differing numbers of electrons in different compounds.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Thus, chemical bonding between these elements takes many forms of electron-sharing that are more than simple electron transfers.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Examples include the element carbon and the organic compounds.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The chemical elements are often displayed in a periodic table that is laid out to display recurring chemical properties, and elements with the same number of valence electrons form a group that is aligned in the same column of the table.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] (The horizontal rows correspond to the filling of a quantum shell of electrons.) The elements at the far right of the table have their outer shell completely filled with electrons, which results in chemically inert elements known as the noble gases.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Quantities of atoms are found in different states of matter that depend on the physical conditions, such as temperature and pressure.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] By varying the conditions, materials can transition between solids, liquids, gases, and plasmas.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Within a state, a material can also exist in different allotropes.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] An example of this is solid carbon, which can exist as graphite or diamond.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Gaseous allotropes exist as well, such as dioxygen and ozone.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] At temperatures close to absolute zero, atoms can form a Bose–Einstein condensate, at which point quantum mechanical effects, which are normally only observed at the atomic scale, become apparent on a macroscopic scale.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] This super-cooled collection of atoms then behaves as a single super atom, which may allow fundamental checks of quantum mechanical behavior.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] While atoms are too small to be seen, devices such as the scanning tunneling microscope (STM) enable their visualization at the surfaces of solids.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The microscope uses the quantum tunneling phenomenon, which allows particles to pass through a barrier that would be insurmountable in the classical perspective.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Electrons tunnel through the vacuum between two biased electrodes, providing a tunneling current that is exponentially dependent on their separation.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] One electrode is a sharp tip ideally ending with a single atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] At each point of the scan of the surface the tip's height is adjusted so as to keep the tunneling current at a set value.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] How much the tip moves to and away from the surface is interpreted as the height profile.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] For low bias, the microscope images the averaged electron orbitals across closely packed energy levels—the local density of the electronic states near the Fermi level.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Because of the distances involved, both electrodes need to be extremely stable; only then periodicities can be observed that correspond to individual atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The method alone is not chemically specific, and cannot identify the atomic species present at the surface.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Atoms can be easily identified by their mass.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If an atom is ionized by removing one of its electrons, its trajectory when it passes through a magnetic field will bend.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The radius by which the trajectory of a moving ion is turned by the magnetic field is determined by the mass of the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The mass spectrometer uses this principle to measure the mass-to-charge ratio of ions.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] If a sample contains multiple isotopes, the mass spectrometer can determine the proportion of each isotope in the sample by measuring the intensity of the different beams of ions.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Techniques to vaporize atoms include inductively coupled plasma atomic emission spectroscopy and inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry, both of which use a plasma to vaporize samples for analysis.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] The atom-probe tomograph has sub-nanometer resolution in 3-D and can chemically identify individual atoms using time-of-flight mass spectrometry.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Electron emission techniques such as X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) and Auger electron spectroscopy (AES), which measure the binding energies of the core electrons, are used to identify the atomic species present in a sample in a non-destructive way.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] With proper focusing both can be made area-specific.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Another such method is electron energy loss spectroscopy (EELS), which measures the energy loss of an electron beam within a transmission electron microscope when it interacts with a portion of a sample.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Spectra of excited states can be used to analyze the atomic composition of distant stars.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Specific light wavelengths contained in the observed light from stars can be separated out and related to the quantized transitions in free gas atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] These colors can be replicated using a gas-discharge lamp containing the same element.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p01] Helium was discovered in this way in the spectrum of the Sun 23 years before it was found on Earth.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Baryonic matter forms about 4% of the total energy density of the observable universe, with an average density of about 0.25 particles/m3 (mostly protons and electrons).
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Within a galaxy such as the Milky Way, particles have a much higher concentration, with the density of matter in the interstellar medium (ISM) ranging from 105 to 109 atoms/m3.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] The Sun is believed to be inside the Local Bubble, so the density in the solar neighborhood is only about 103 atoms/m3.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Stars form from dense clouds in the ISM, and the evolutionary processes of stars result in the steady enrichment of the ISM with elements more massive than hydrogen and helium.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Up to 95% of the Milky Way's baryonic matter are concentrated inside stars, where conditions are unfavorable for atomic matter.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] The total baryonic mass is about 10% of the mass of the galaxy; the remainder of the mass is an unknown dark matter.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] High temperature inside stars makes most "atoms" fully ionized, that is, separates *all* electrons from the nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] In stellar remnants—with exception of their surface layers—an immense pressure make electron shells impossible.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Electrons are thought to exist in the Universe since early stages of the Big Bang.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Atomic nuclei forms in nucleosynthesis reactions.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] In about three minutes Big Bang nucleosynthesis produced most of the helium, lithium, and deuterium in the Universe, and perhaps some of the beryllium and boron.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Ubiquitousness and stability of atoms relies on their binding energy, which means that an atom has a lower energy than an unbound system of the nucleus and electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Where the temperature is much higher than ionization potential, the matter exists in the form of plasma—a gas of positively charged ions (possibly, bare nuclei) and electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] When the temperature drops below the ionization potential, atoms become statistically favorable.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Atoms (complete with bound electrons) became to dominate over charged particles 380,000 years after the Big Bang—an epoch called recombination, when the expanding Universe cooled enough to allow electrons to become attached to nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Isotopes such as lithium-6, as well as some beryllium and boron are generated in space through cosmic ray spallation.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] This occurs when a high-energy proton strikes an atomic nucleus, causing large numbers of nucleons to be ejected.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Elements heavier than iron were produced in supernovae and colliding neutron stars through the r-process, and in AGB stars through the s-process, both of which involve the capture of neutrons by atomic nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Elements such as lead formed largely through the radioactive decay of heavier elements.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Most of the atoms that make up the Earth and its inhabitants were present in their current form in the nebula that collapsed out of a molecular cloud to form the Solar System.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] The rest are the result of radioactive decay, and their relative proportion can be used to determine the age of the Earth through radiometric dating.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Most of the helium in the crust of the Earth (about 99% of the helium from gas wells, as shown by its lower abundance of helium-3) is a product of alpha decay.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] There are a few trace atoms on Earth that were not present at the beginning (i.e., not "primordial"), nor are results of radioactive decay.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Carbon-14 is continuously generated by cosmic rays in the atmosphere.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Some atoms on Earth have been artificially generated either deliberately or as by-products of nuclear reactors or explosions.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Of the transuranic elements—those with atomic numbers greater than 92—only plutonium and neptunium occur naturally on Earth.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Transuranic elements have radioactive lifetimes shorter than the current age of the Earth and thus identifiable quantities of these elements have long since decayed, with the exception of traces of plutonium-244 possibly deposited by cosmic dust.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Natural deposits of plutonium and neptunium are produced by neutron capture in uranium ore.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] The Earth contains approximately 1.33×1050 atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Although small numbers of independent atoms of noble gases exist, such as argon, neon, and helium, 99% of the atmosphere is bound in the form of molecules, including carbon dioxide and diatomic oxygen and nitrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] At the surface of the Earth, an overwhelming majority of atoms combine to form various compounds, including water, salt, silicates, and oxides.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Atoms can also combine to create materials that do not consist of discrete molecules, including crystals and liquid or solid metals.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] This atomic matter forms networked arrangements that lack the particular type of small-scale interrupted order associated with molecular matter.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] All nuclides with atomic numbers higher than 82 (lead) are known to be radioactive.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] No nuclide with an atomic number exceeding 92 (uranium) exists on Earth as a primordial nuclide, and heavier elements generally have shorter half-lives.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Nevertheless, an "island of stability" encompassing relatively long-lived isotopes of superheavy elements with atomic numbers 110 to 114 might exist.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Predictions for the half-life of the most stable nuclide on the island range from a few minutes to millions of years.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] In any case, superheavy elements (with *Z* > 104) would not exist due to increasing Coulomb repulsion (which results in spontaneous fission with increasingly short half-lives) in the absence of any stabilizing effects.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Each particle of matter has a corresponding antimatter particle with the opposite electrical charge.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Thus, the positron is a positively charged antielectron and the antiproton is a negatively charged equivalent of a proton.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] When a matter and corresponding antimatter particle meet, they annihilate each other.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Because of this, along with an imbalance between the number of matter and antimatter particles, the latter are rare in the universe.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] The first causes of this imbalance are not yet fully understood, although theories of baryogenesis may offer an explanation.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] As a result, no antimatter atoms have been discovered in nature.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] In 1996, the antimatter counterpart of the hydrogen atom (antihydrogen) was synthesized at the CERN laboratory in Geneva.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] Other exotic atoms have been created by replacing one of the protons, neutrons or electrons with other particles that have the same charge.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] For example, an electron can be replaced by a more massive muon, forming a muonic atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atom-p02] These types of atoms can be used to test fundamental predictions of physics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In quantum mechanics, an **atomic orbital** is a function describing the location and wave-like behavior of an electron in an atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This function describes an electron's charge distribution around the atom's nucleus, and can be used to calculate the probability of finding an electron in a specific region around the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Each orbital in an atom is characterized by a set of values of three quantum numbers n, ℓ, and mℓ, which respectively correspond to an electron's energy, its orbital angular momentum, and its orbital angular momentum projected along a chosen axis (magnetic quantum number).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The orbitals with a well-defined magnetic quantum number are generally complex-valued.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Real-valued orbitals can be formed as linear combinations of mℓ and −mℓ orbitals, and are often labeled using associated harmonic polynomials (e.g., *xy*, *x*2 − *y*2) which describe their angular structure.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] An orbital can be occupied by a maximum of two electrons, each with its own projection of spin $m_{s}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The simple names **s orbital**, **p orbital**, **d orbital**, and **f orbital** refer to orbitals with angular momentum quantum number *ℓ* = 0, 1, 2, and 3 respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These names, together with their n values, are used to describe electron configurations of atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] They are derived from description by early spectroscopists of certain series of alkali metal spectroscopic lines as sharp, principal, diffuse, and fundamental.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Orbitals for *ℓ* > 3 continue alphabetically (g, h, i, k, ...), omitting j because some languages do not distinguish between letters "i" and "j".
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Atomic orbitals are basic building blocks of the **atomic orbital model** (or electron cloud or wave mechanics model), a modern framework for visualizing submicroscopic behavior of electrons in matter.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In this model, the electron cloud of an atom may be seen as being built up (in approximation) in an electron configuration that is a product of simpler hydrogen-like atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] With the development of quantum mechanics and experimental findings (such as the two slit diffraction of electrons), it was found that the electrons orbiting a nucleus could not be fully described as particles, but needed to be explained by wave–particle duality.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The electrons are never in a single point location, though the probability of interacting with the electron at a single point can be found from the electron's wave function.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The electron's charge acts like it is smeared out in space in a continuous distribution, proportional at any point to the squared magnitude of the electron's wave function.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Electrons jump between orbitals like particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For example, if one photon strikes the electrons, only one electron changes state as a result.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Electrons retain particle-like properties such as: each wave state has the same electric charge as its electron particle.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Each wave state has a single discrete spin (spin up or spin down) depending on its superposition.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Thus, electrons cannot be described simply as solid particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] An analogy might be that of a large and often oddly shaped "atmosphere" (the electron), distributed around a relatively tiny planet (the nucleus).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Atomic orbitals exactly describe the shape of this "atmosphere" only when one electron is present.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] One should remember that these orbital 'states', as described here, are merely eigenstates of an electron in its orbit.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] An actual electron exists in a superposition of states, which is like a weighted average, but with complex number weights.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For each eigenstate, a property has an eigenvalue.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Therefore, for the three states just mentioned, the value of n is 2, and the value of l is 1.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For the second and third states, the value for $m_{l}$ is a superposition of 0 and 1.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] As a superposition of states, it is ambiguous—either exactly 0 or exactly 1—not an intermediate or average value like the fraction ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] A superposition of eigenstates (2, 1, 1) and (3, 2, 1) would have an ambiguous n and l , but $m_{l}$ would definitely be 1.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Eigenstates make it easier to deal with the math.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] You can choose a different basis of eigenstates by superimposing eigenstates from any other basis (see Real orbitals below).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Atomic orbitals may be defined more precisely in formal quantum mechanical language.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] They are approximate solutions to the Schrödinger equation for the electrons bound to the atom by the electric field of the atom's nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Specifically, in quantum mechanics, the state of an atom, i.e., an eigenstate of the atomic Hamiltonian, is approximated by an expansion (see configuration interaction expansion and basis set) into linear combinations of anti-symmetrized products (Slater determinants) of one-electron functions.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The spatial components of these one-electron functions are called atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In atomic physics, the atomic spectral lines correspond to transitions (quantum leaps) between quantum states of an atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These states are labeled by a set of quantum numbers summarized in the term symbol and usually associated with particular electron configurations, i.e., by occupation schemes of atomic orbitals (for example, 1s2 2s2 2p6 for the ground state of neon-term symbol: 1S0).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This notation means that the corresponding Slater determinants have a clear higher weight in the configuration interaction expansion.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The atomic orbital concept is therefore a key concept for visualizing the excitation process associated with a given transition.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For example, one can say for a given transition that it corresponds to the excitation of an electron from an occupied orbital to a given unoccupied orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Nevertheless, one has to keep in mind that electrons are fermions ruled by the Pauli exclusion principle and cannot be distinguished from each other.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Moreover, it sometimes happens that the configuration interaction expansion converges very slowly and that one cannot speak about simple one-determinant wave function at all.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This is the case when electron correlation is large.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Fundamentally, an atomic orbital is a one-electron wave function, even though many electrons are not in one-electron atoms, and so the one-electron view is an approximation.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] When thinking about orbitals, we are often given an orbital visualization heavily influenced by the Hartree–Fock approximation, which is one way to reduce the complexities of molecular orbital theory.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Atomic orbitals can be the hydrogen-like "orbitals" which are exact solutions to the Schrödinger equation for a hydrogen-like "atom" (i.e., atom with one electron).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Alternatively, atomic orbitals refer to functions that depend on the coordinates of one electron (i.e., orbitals) but are used as starting points for approximating wave functions that depend on the simultaneous coordinates of all the electrons in an atom or molecule.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The coordinate systems chosen for orbitals are usually spherical coordinates (*r*, *θ*, *φ*) in atoms and Cartesian (*x*, *y*, *z*) in polyatomic molecules.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The advantage of spherical coordinates here is that an orbital wave function is a product of three factors each dependent on a single coordinate: *ψ*(*r*, *θ*, *φ*) = *R*(*r*) Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The angular factors of atomic orbitals Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*) generate s, p, d, etc. functions as real combinations of spherical harmonics *Y**ℓm*(*θ*, *φ*) (where ℓ and m are quantum numbers).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The Slater-type orbital (STO) is a form without radial nodes but decays from the nucleus as does a hydrogen-like orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The form of the Gaussian type orbital (Gaussians) has no radial nodes and decays as $e^{-\alpha r^{2}}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Although hydrogen-like orbitals are still used as pedagogical tools, the advent of computers has made STOs preferable for atoms and diatomic molecules since combinations of STOs can replace the nodes in hydrogen-like orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Gaussians are typically used in molecules with three or more atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Although not as accurate by themselves as STOs, combinations of many Gaussians can attain the accuracy of hydrogen-like orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The term *orbital* was introduced by Robert S.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Mulliken in 1932 as short for *one-electron orbital wave function*.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Niels Bohr explained around 1913 that electrons might revolve around a compact nucleus with definite angular momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Bohr's model was an improvement on the 1911 explanations of Ernest Rutherford, that of the electron moving around a nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Japanese physicist Hantaro Nagaoka published an orbit-based hypothesis for electron behavior as early as 1904.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These theories were each built upon new observations starting with simple understanding and becoming more correct and complex.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Explaining the behavior of these electron "orbits" was one of the driving forces behind the development of quantum mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Thomson's discovery of the electron in 1897, it became clear that atoms were not the smallest building blocks of nature, but were rather composite particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The newly discovered structure within atoms tempted many to imagine how the atom's constituent parts might interact with each other.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Thomson theorized that multiple electrons revolve in orbit-like rings within a positively charged jelly-like substance, and between the electron's discovery and 1909, this "plum pudding model" was the most widely accepted explanation of atomic structure.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Shortly after Thomson's discovery, Hantaro Nagaoka predicted a different model for electronic structure.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Unlike the plum pudding model, the positive charge in Nagaoka's "Saturnian Model" was concentrated into a central core, pulling the electrons into circular orbits reminiscent of Saturn's rings.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Few people took notice of Nagaoka's work at the time, and Nagaoka himself recognized a fundamental defect in the theory even at its conception, namely that a classical charged object cannot sustain orbital motion because it is accelerating and therefore loses energy due to electromagnetic radiation.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Nevertheless, the Saturnian model turned out to have more in common with modern theory than any of its contemporaries.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In 1909, Ernest Rutherford discovered that the bulk of the atomic mass was tightly condensed into a nucleus, which was also found to be positively charged.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] It became clear from his analysis in 1911 that the plum pudding model could not explain atomic structure.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In 1913, Rutherford's post-doctoral student, Niels Bohr, proposed a new model of the atom, wherein electrons orbited the nucleus with classical periods, but were permitted to have only discrete values of angular momentum, quantized in units ħ.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This constraint automatically allowed only certain electron energies.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The Bohr model of the atom fixed the problem of energy loss from radiation from a ground state (by declaring that there was no state below this), and more importantly explained the origin of spectral lines.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The most prominent feature of emission and absorption spectra (known experimentally since the middle of the 19th century), was that these atomic spectra contained discrete lines.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The significance of the Bohr model was that it related the lines in emission and absorption spectra to the energy differences between the orbits that electrons could take around an atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This was, however, *not* achieved by Bohr through giving the electrons some kind of wave-like properties, since the idea that electrons could behave as matter waves was not suggested until eleven years later.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The Bohr model for a short time could be seen as a classical model with an additional constraint provided by the 'wavelength' argument.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] However, this period was immediately superseded by the full three-dimensional wave mechanics of 1926.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In our current understanding of physics, the Bohr model is called a semi-classical model because of its quantization of angular momentum, not primarily because of its relationship with electron wavelength, which appeared in hindsight a dozen years after the Bohr model was proposed.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The Bohr model was able to explain the emission and absorption spectra of hydrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The energies of electrons in the *n* = 1, 2, 3, etc. states in the Bohr model match those of current physics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] However, this did not explain similarities between different atoms, as expressed by the periodic table, such as the fact that helium (two electrons), neon (10 electrons), and argon (18 electrons) exhibit similar chemical inertness.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Modern quantum mechanics explains this in terms of electron shells and subshells which can each hold a number of electrons determined by the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Thus the *n* = 1 state can hold one or two electrons, while the *n* = 2 state can hold up to eight electrons in 2s and 2p subshells.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In helium, all *n* = 1 states are fully occupied; the same is true for *n* = 1 and *n* = 2 in neon.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In argon, the 3s and 3p subshells are similarly fully occupied by eight electrons; quantum mechanics also allows a 3d subshell but this is at higher energy than the 3s and 3p in argon (contrary to the situation for hydrogen) and remains empty.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Immediately after Heisenberg discovered his uncertainty principle, Bohr noted that the existence of any sort of wave packet implies uncertainty in the wave frequency and wavelength, since a spread of frequencies is needed to create the packet itself.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In quantum mechanics, where all particle momenta are associated with waves, it is the formation of such a wave packet which localizes the wave, and thus the particle, in space.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In states where a quantum mechanical particle is bound, it must be localized as a wave packet, and the existence of the packet and its minimum size implies a spread and minimal value in particle wavelength, and thus also momentum and energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In quantum mechanics, as a particle is localized to a smaller region in space, the associated compressed wave packet requires a larger and larger range of momenta, and thus larger kinetic energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Thus the binding energy to contain or trap a particle in a smaller region of space increases without bound as the region of space grows smaller.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Particles cannot be restricted to a geometric point in space, since this would require infinite particle momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In chemistry, Erwin Schrödinger, Linus Pauling, Mulliken and others noted that the consequence of Heisenberg's relation was that the electron, as a wave packet, could not be considered to have an exact location in its orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Max Born suggested that the electron's position needed to be described by a probability distribution which was connected with finding the electron at some point in the wave-function which described its associated wave packet.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The new quantum mechanics did not give exact results, but only the probabilities for the occurrence of a variety of possible such results.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Heisenberg held that the path of a moving particle has no meaning if we cannot observe it, as we cannot with electrons in an atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] where *X* is the energy level corresponding to the principal quantum number n; **type** is a lower-case letter denoting the shape or subshell of the orbital, corresponding to the angular momentum quantum number ℓ.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For example, the orbital 1s (pronounced as the individual numbers and letters: "'one' 'ess'") is the lowest energy level (*n* = 1) and has an angular quantum number of *ℓ* = 0, denoted as s.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Orbitals with *ℓ* = 1, 2 and 3 are denoted as p, d and f respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The superscript y shows the number of electrons in the subshell.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For example, the notation 2p4 indicates that the 2p subshell of an atom contains 4 electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This subshell has 3 orbitals, each with n = 2 and ℓ = 1.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] There is also another, less common system still used in X-ray science known as X-ray notation, which is a continuation of the notations used before orbital theory was well understood.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In this system, the principal quantum number is given a letter associated with it.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For *n* = 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, ..., the letters associated with those numbers are K, L, M, N, O, ... respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The simplest atomic orbitals are those that are calculated for systems with a single electron, such as the hydrogen atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] An atom of any other element ionized down to a single electron (He+, Li2+, etc.) is very similar to hydrogen, and the orbitals take the same form.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In the Schrödinger equation for this system of one negative and one positive particle, the atomic orbitals are the eigenstates of the Hamiltonian operator for the energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] They can be obtained analytically, meaning that the resulting orbitals are products of a polynomial series, and exponential and trigonometric functions.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For atoms with two or more electrons, the governing equations can be solved only with the use of methods of iterative approximation.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Orbitals of multi-electron atoms are *qualitatively* similar to those of hydrogen, and in the simplest models, they are taken to have the same form.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For more rigorous and precise analysis, numerical approximations must be used.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] A given (hydrogen-like) atomic orbital is identified by unique values of three quantum numbers: n, ℓ, and mℓ.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The rules restricting the values of the quantum numbers, and their energies (see below), explain the electron configuration of the atoms and the periodic table.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The stationary states (quantum states) of a hydrogen-like atom are its atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] However, in general, an electron's behavior is not fully described by a single orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Electron states are best represented by time-depending "mixtures" (linear combinations) of multiple orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] See Linear combination of atomic orbitals molecular orbital method.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The quantum number n first appeared in the Bohr model where it determines the radius of each circular electron orbit.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In modern quantum mechanics however, the mean distance of the electron from the nucleus primarily depends on n.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For this reason, orbitals with the same value of *n* are said to comprise a "shell".
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Orbitals with the same value of *n* and also the same value of ℓ have the same average distance from the nucleus and are said to comprise a "subshell".
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Because of the quantum mechanical nature of the electrons around a nucleus, atomic orbitals can be uniquely defined by a set of integers known as quantum numbers.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These quantum numbers occur only in certain combinations of values, and their physical interpretation changes depending on whether real or complex versions of the atomic orbitals are employed.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In physics, the most common orbital descriptions are based on the solutions to the hydrogen atom, where orbitals are given by the product between a radial function and a pure spherical harmonic.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The principal quantum number n describes the energy of the electron and is always a positive integer.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In fact, it can be any positive integer, but for reasons discussed below, large numbers are seldom encountered.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Each atom has, in general, many orbitals associated with each value of *n*; these orbitals together are sometimes called *electron shells*.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The azimuthal quantum number ℓ describes the orbital angular momentum of each electron and is a non-negative integer.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Within a shell where n is some integer *n*0, ℓ ranges across all (integer) values satisfying the relation $0\leq \ell \leq n_{0}-1$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For instance, the *n* = 1 shell has only orbitals with $\ell =0$ , and the *n* = 2 shell has only orbitals with $\ell =0$ , and $\ell =1$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The set of orbitals associated with a particular value of ℓ are sometimes collectively called a *subshell*.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The magnetic quantum number, $m_{\ell }$ , describes the projection of the orbital angular momentum along a chosen axis.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] It determines the magnitude of the current circulating around that axis and the orbital contribution to the magnetic moment of an electron via the Ampèrian loop model.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Within a subshell $\ell$ , $m_{\ell }$ obtains the integer values in the range $-\ell \leq m_{\ell }\leq \ell$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The above results may be summarized in the following table.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Each cell represents a subshell, and lists the values of $m_{\ell }$ available in that subshell.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Empty cells represent subshells that do not exist.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Subshells are usually identified by their n - and $\ell$ -values. n is represented by its numerical value, but $\ell$ is represented by a letter as follows: 0 is represented by 's', 1 by 'p', 2 by 'd', 3 by 'f', and 4 by 'g'.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For instance, one may speak of the subshell with $n=2$ and $\ell =0$ as a '2s subshell'.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Each electron also has angular momentum in the form of quantum mechanical spin given by spin *s* = ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Its projection along a specified axis is given by the spin magnetic quantum number, *ms*, which can be +⁠1/2⁠ or −⁠1/2⁠.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These values are also called "spin up" or "spin down" respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The Pauli exclusion principle states that no two electrons in an atom can have the same values of all four quantum numbers.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] If there are two electrons in an orbital with given values for three quantum numbers, (n, ℓ, m), these two electrons must differ in their spin projection *ms*.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The above conventions imply a preferred axis (for example, the *z* direction in Cartesian coordinates), and they also imply a preferred direction along this preferred axis.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Otherwise there would be no sense in distinguishing *m* = +1 from *m* = −1.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] As such, the model is most useful when applied to physical systems that share these symmetries.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The Stern–Gerlach experiment—where an atom is exposed to a magnetic field—provides one such example.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Instead of the complex orbitals described above, it is common, especially in the chemistry literature, to use *real* atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These real orbitals arise from simple linear combinations of complex orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Using the Condon–Shortley phase convention, real orbitals are related to complex orbitals in the same way that the real spherical harmonics are related to complex spherical harmonics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Real spherical harmonics are physically relevant when an atom is embedded in a crystalline solid, in which case there are multiple preferred symmetry axes but no single preferred direction.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Real atomic orbitals are also more frequently encountered in introductory chemistry textbooks and shown in common orbital visualizations.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In real hydrogen-like orbitals, quantum numbers n and ℓ have the same interpretation and significance as their complex counterparts, but m is no longer a good quantum number (but its absolute value is).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Some real orbitals are given specific names beyond the simple $\psi _{n,\ell ,m}$ designation.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] With this one can already assign names to complex orbitals such as $2{\text{p}}_{\pm 1}=\psi _{2,1,\pm 1}$ ; the first symbol is the n quantum number, the second character is the symbol for that particular ℓ quantum number and the subscript is the m quantum number.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] As an example of how the full orbital names are generated for real orbitals, one may calculate $\psi _{n,1,\pm 1}^{\text{real}}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In all these cases we generate a Cartesian label for the orbital by examining, and abbreviating, the polynomial in *x*, *y*, *z* appearing in the numerator.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] We ignore any terms in the *z*, *r* polynomial except for the term with the highest exponent in z.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] We then use the abbreviated polynomial as a subscript label for the atomic state, using the same nomenclature as above to indicate the n and $\ell$ quantum numbers.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The expressions above all use the Condon–Shortley phase convention which is favored by quantum physicists.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Other conventions exist for the phase of the spherical harmonics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Under these different conventions the ${\text{p}}_{x}$ and ${\text{p}}_{y}$ orbitals may appear, for example, as the sum and difference of ${\text{p}}_{+1}$ and ${\text{p}}_{-1}$ , contrary to what is shown above.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Below is a list of these Cartesian polynomial names for the atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] There does not seem to be reference in the literature as to how to abbreviate the long Cartesian spherical harmonic polynomials for $\ell >3$ so there does not seem be consensus on the naming of g orbitals or higher according to this nomenclature.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Simple pictures showing orbital shapes are intended to describe the angular forms of regions in space where the electrons occupying the orbital are likely to be found.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The diagrams cannot show the entire region where an electron can be found, since according to quantum mechanics there is a non-zero probability of finding the electron (almost) anywhere in space.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Instead the diagrams are approximate representations of boundary or contour surfaces where the probability density | ψ(*r*, *θ*, *φ*) |2 has a constant value, chosen so that there is a certain probability (for example 90%) of finding the electron within the contour.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Although | *ψ* |2 as the square of an absolute value is everywhere non-negative, the sign of the wave function ψ(*r*, *θ*, *φ*) is often indicated in each subregion of the orbital picture.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This article, to show wave function phase, shows mostly ψ(*r*, *θ*, *φ*) graphs.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The lobes can be seen as standing wave interference patterns between the two counter-rotating, ring-resonant traveling wave m and −*m* modes; the projection of the orbital onto the xy plane has a resonant m wavelength around the circumference.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Although rarely shown, the traveling wave solutions can be seen as rotating banded tori; the bands represent phase information.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For each m there are two standing wave solutions ⟨*m*⟩ + ⟨−*m*⟩ and ⟨*m*⟩ − ⟨−*m*⟩.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] If *m* = 0, the orbital is vertical, counter rotating information is unknown, and the orbital is *z*-axis symmetric.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] If *ℓ* = 0 there are no counter rotating modes.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] There are only radial modes and the shape is spherically symmetric.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In general, n determines size and energy of the orbital for a given nucleus; as n increases, the size of the orbital increases.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The higher nuclear charge Z of heavier elements causes their orbitals to contract by comparison to lighter ones, so that the size of the atom remains very roughly constant, even as the number of electrons increases.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Also in general terms, ℓ determines an orbital's shape, and mℓ its orientation.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] However, since some orbitals are described by equations in complex numbers, the shape sometimes depends on mℓ also.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Together, the whole set of orbitals for a given ℓ and n fill space as symmetrically as possible, though with increasingly complex sets of lobes and nodes.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The single s orbitals ( $\ell =0$ ) are shaped like spheres.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For *n* = 1 it is roughly a solid ball (densest at center and fades outward exponentially), but for *n* ≥ 2, each single s orbital is made of spherically symmetric surfaces which are nested shells (i.e., the "wave-structure" is radial, following a sinusoidal radial component as well).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] See illustration of a cross-section of these nested shells, at right.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The s orbitals for all n numbers are the only orbitals with an anti-node (a region of high wave function density) at the center of the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] All other orbitals (p, d, f, etc.) have angular momentum, and thus avoid the nucleus (having a wave node *at* the nucleus).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Recently, there has been an effort to experimentally image the 1s and 2p orbitals in a SrTiO3 crystal using scanning transmission electron microscopy with energy dispersive x-ray spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Because the imaging was conducted using an electron beam, Coulombic beam-orbital interaction that is often termed as the impact parameter effect is included in the outcome (see the figure at right).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The shapes of p, d and f orbitals are described verbally here and shown graphically in the *Orbitals table* below.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The three p orbitals for *n* = 2 have the form of two ellipsoids with a point of tangency at the nucleus (the two-lobed shape is sometimes referred to as a "dumbbell"—there are two lobes pointing in opposite directions from each other).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The three p orbitals in each shell are oriented at right angles to each other, as determined by their respective linear combination of values of mℓ.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The overall result is a lobe pointing along each direction of the primary axes.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Four of the five d orbitals for *n* = 3 look similar, each with four pear-shaped lobes, each lobe tangent at right angles to two others, and the centers of all four lying in one plane.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Three of these planes are the xy-, xz-, and yz-planes—the lobes are between the pairs of primary axes—and the fourth has the center along the x and y axes themselves.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The fifth and final d orbital consists of three regions of high probability density: a torus in between two pear-shaped regions placed symmetrically on its z axis.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The overall total of 18 directional lobes point in every primary axis direction and between every pair.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] There are seven f orbitals, each with shapes more complex than those of the d orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Additionally, as is the case with the s orbitals, individual p, d, f and g orbitals with n values higher than the lowest possible value, exhibit an additional radial node structure which is reminiscent of harmonic waves of the same type, as compared with the lowest (or fundamental) mode of the wave.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] As with s orbitals, this phenomenon provides p, d, f, and g orbitals at the next higher possible value of n (for example, 3p orbitals vs. the fundamental 2p), an additional node in each lobe.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Still higher values of n further increase the number of radial nodes, for each type of orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The shapes of atomic orbitals in a one-electron atom are related to 3-dimensional spherical harmonics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These shapes are not unique, and any linear combination is valid, like a transformation to cubic harmonics, in fact it is possible to generate sets where all the d's are the same shape, just like the p*x*, p*y*, and p*z* are the same shape.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Although individual orbitals are most often shown independent of each other, the orbitals coexist around the nucleus at the same time.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This table shows the real hydrogen-like wave functions for all atomic orbitals up to 7s, and therefore covers the occupied orbitals in the ground state of all elements in the periodic table up to radium.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] "ψ" graphs are shown with **−** and **+** wave function phases shown in two different colors (arbitrarily red and blue).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The p*z* orbital is the same as the p0 orbital, but the p*x* and p*y* are formed by taking linear combinations of the p+1 and p−1 orbitals (which is why they are listed under the *m* = ±1 label).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Also, the p+1 and p−1 are not the same shape as the p0, since they are pure spherical harmonics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] ‡ *For the elements whose highest occupied orbital is a 6d orbital, only some electronic configurations have been confirmed.* (Mt, Ds, Rg and Cn are still missing).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These are the real-valued orbitals commonly used in chemistry.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Only the $m=0$ orbitals where are eigenstates of the orbital angular momentum operator, ${\hat {L}}_{z}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The columns with $m=\pm 1,\pm 2,\cdots$ are combinations of two eigenstates.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The shapes of atomic orbitals can be qualitatively understood by considering the analogous case of standing waves on a circular drum.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] To see the analogy, the mean vibrational displacement of each bit of drum membrane from the equilibrium point over many cycles (a measure of average drum membrane velocity and momentum at that point) must be considered relative to that point's distance from the center of the drum head.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] If this displacement is taken as being analogous to the probability of finding an electron at a given distance from the nucleus, then it will be seen that the many modes of the vibrating disk form patterns that trace the various shapes of atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] The basic reason for this correspondence lies in the fact that the distribution of kinetic energy and momentum in a matter-wave is predictive of where the particle associated with the wave will be.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This relationship means that certain key features can be observed in both drum membrane modes and atomic orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For example, in all of the modes analogous to **s** orbitals (the top row in the animated illustration below), it can be seen that the very center of the drum membrane vibrates most strongly, corresponding to the antinode in all **s** orbitals in an atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] This antinode means the electron is most likely to be at the physical position of the nucleus (which it passes straight through without scattering or striking it), since it is moving (on average) most rapidly at that point, giving it maximal momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Below, a number of drum membrane vibration modes and the respective wave functions of the hydrogen atom are shown.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] A correspondence can be considered where the wave functions of a vibrating drum head are for a two-coordinate system ψ(*r*, *θ*) and the wave functions for a vibrating sphere are three-coordinate ψ(*r*, *θ*, *φ*).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] None of the other sets of modes in a drum membrane have a central antinode, and in all of them the center of the drum does not move.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These correspond to a node at the nucleus for all non-**s** orbitals in an atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] These orbitals all have some angular momentum, and in the planetary model, they correspond to particles in orbit with eccentricity less than 1.0, so that they do not pass straight through the center of the primary body, but keep somewhat away from it.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] In addition, the drum modes analogous to **p** and **d** modes in an atom show spatial irregularity along the different radial directions from the center of the drum, whereas all of the modes analogous to **s** modes are perfectly symmetrical in radial direction.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] For these modes, waves in the drum head tend to avoid the central point.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p01] Such features again emphasize that the shapes of atomic orbitals are a direct consequence of the wave nature of electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] In atoms with one electron (hydrogen-like atom), the energy of an orbital (and, consequently, any electron in the orbital) is determined mainly by n .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The $n=1$ orbital has the lowest possible energy in the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Each successively higher value of n has a higher energy, but the difference decreases as n increases.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] For high n , the energy becomes so high that the electron can easily escape the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] In single electron atoms, all levels with different $\ell$ within a given n are degenerate in the Schrödinger approximation, and have the same energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] This approximation is broken slightly in the solution to the Dirac equation (where energy depends on n and another quantum number j), and by the effect of the magnetic field of the nucleus and quantum electrodynamics effects.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The latter induce tiny binding energy differences especially for **s** electrons that go nearer the nucleus, since these feel a very slightly different nuclear charge, even in one-electron atoms; see Lamb shift.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] In atoms with multiple electrons, the energy of an electron depends not only on its orbital, but also on its interactions with other electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] These interactions depend on the detail of its spatial probability distribution, and so the energy levels of orbitals depend not only on n but also on $\ell$ .
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Higher values of $\ell$ are associated with higher values of energy; for instance, the 2p state is higher than the 2s state.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] When $\ell =2$ , the increase in energy of the orbital becomes so large as to push the energy of orbital above the energy of the s orbital in the next higher shell; when $\ell =3$ the energy is pushed into the shell two steps higher.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The filling of the 3d orbitals does not occur until the 4s orbitals have been filled, and the filling of the 4f orbitals does not occur all the way until the 6s orbitals have been filled.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Thus, in atoms with higher atomic number, the $\ell$ of electrons becomes more and more of a determining factor in their energy, and the principal quantum numbers n of electrons becomes less and less important in their energy placement.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The energy sequence of the first 35 subshells (e.g., 1s, 2p, 3d, etc.) is given in the following table.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Each cell represents a subshell with n and $\ell$ given by its row and column indices, respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The number in the cell is the subshell's position in the sequence.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] For a linear listing of the subshells in terms of increasing energies in multielectron atoms, see the section below.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Several rules govern the placement of electrons in orbitals (*electron configuration*).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The first dictates that no two electrons in an atom may have the same set of values of quantum numbers (this is the Pauli exclusion principle).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] These quantum numbers include the three that define orbitals, as well as the spin magnetic quantum number ms.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Thus, two electrons may occupy a single orbital, so long as they have different values of ms.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Because ms takes one of only two values (⁠1/2⁠ or −⁠1/2⁠), at most two electrons can occupy each orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Additionally, an electron always tends to fall to the lowest possible energy state.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] It is possible for it to occupy any orbital so long as it does not violate the Pauli exclusion principle, but if lower-energy orbitals are available, this condition is unstable.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The electron will eventually lose energy (by releasing a photon) and drop into the lower orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Thus, electrons fill orbitals in the order specified by the energy sequence given above.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] This behavior is responsible for the structure of the periodic table.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The table may be divided into several rows (called 'periods'), numbered starting with 1 at the top.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The presently known elements occupy seven periods.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] If a certain period has number *i*, it consists of elements whose outermost electrons fall in the *i*th shell.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Niels Bohr was the first to propose (1923) that the periodicity in the properties of the elements might be explained by the periodic filling of the electron energy levels, resulting in the electronic structure of the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The periodic table may also be divided into several numbered rectangular 'blocks'.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The elements belonging to a given block have this common feature: their highest-energy electrons all belong to the same ℓ-state (but the n associated with that ℓ-state depends upon the period).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] For instance, the leftmost two columns constitute the 's-block'.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The outermost electrons of Li and Be respectively belong to the 2s subshell, and those of Na and Mg to the 3s subshell.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The "periodic" nature of the filling of orbitals, as well as emergence of the **s**, **p**, **d**, and **f** "blocks", is more obvious if this order of filling is given in matrix form, with increasing principal quantum numbers starting the new rows ("periods") in the matrix.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Then, each subshell (composed of the first two quantum numbers) is repeated as many times as required for each pair of electrons it may contain.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Although this is the general order of orbital filling according to the Madelung rule, there are exceptions, and the actual electronic energies of each element are also dependent upon additional details of the atoms (see Electron configuration § Atoms: Aufbau principle and Madelung rule).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The number of electrons in an electrically neutral atom increases with the atomic number.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The electrons in the outermost shell, or *valence electrons*, tend to be responsible for an element's chemical behavior.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Elements that contain the same number of valence electrons can be grouped together and display similar chemical properties.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] For elements with high atomic number Z, the effects of relativity become more pronounced, and especially so for s electrons, which move at relativistic velocities as they penetrate the screening electrons near the core of high-Z atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Examples of significant physical outcomes of this effect include the lowered melting temperature of mercury (which results from 6s electrons not being available for metal bonding) and the golden color of gold and caesium.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] In the Bohr model, an *n* = 1 electron has a velocity given by *v* = *Zαc*, where *Z* is the atomic number, *α* is the fine-structure constant, and *c* is the speed of light.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] In non-relativistic quantum mechanics, therefore, any atom with an atomic number greater than 137 would require its 1s electrons to be traveling faster than the speed of light.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Even in the Dirac equation, which accounts for relativistic effects, the wave function of the electron for atoms with *Z* > 137 is oscillatory and unbounded.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The significance of element 137, also known as untriseptium, was first pointed out by the physicist Richard Feynman.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Element 137 is sometimes informally called feynmanium (symbol Fy).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] However, Feynman's approximation fails to predict the exact critical value of Z due to the non-point-charge nature of the nucleus and very small orbital radius of inner electrons, resulting in a potential seen by inner electrons which is effectively less than Z.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The critical Z value, which makes the atom unstable with regard to high-field breakdown of the vacuum and production of electron–positron pairs, does not occur until Z is about 173.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] These conditions are not seen except transiently in collisions of very heavy nuclei such as lead or uranium in accelerators, where such electron–positron production from these effects has been claimed to be observed.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] There are no nodes in relativistic orbital densities, although individual components of the wave function will have nodes.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] In late period 8 elements, a hybrid of 8p3/2 and 9p1/2 is expected to exist, where "3/2" and "1/2" refer to the total angular momentum quantum number.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] This "pp" hybrid may be responsible for the p-block of the period due to properties similar to p subshells in ordinary valence shells.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Energy levels of 8p3/2 and 9p1/2 come close due to relativistic spin–orbit effects; the 9s subshell should also participate, as these elements are expected to be analogous to the respective 5p elements indium through xenon.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Bound quantum states have discrete energy levels.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] When applied to atomic orbitals, this means that the energy differences between states are also discrete.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] A transition between these states (i.e., an electron absorbing or emitting a photon) can thus happen only if the photon has an energy corresponding with the exact energy difference between said states.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] By quantum theory, state 1 has a fixed energy of *E*1, and state 2 has a fixed energy of *E*2.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Now, what would happen if an electron in state 1 were to move to state 2?
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] For this to happen, the electron would need to gain an energy of exactly *E*2 − *E*1.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] If the electron receives energy that is less than or greater than this value, it cannot jump from state 1 to state 2.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Now, suppose we irradiate the atom with a broad-spectrum of light.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] Photons that reach the atom that have an energy of exactly *E*2 − *E*1 will be absorbed by the electron in state 1, and that electron will jump to state 2.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] However, photons that are greater or lower in energy cannot be absorbed by the electron, because the electron can jump only to one of the orbitals, it cannot jump to a state between orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The result is that only photons of a specific frequency will be absorbed by the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] This creates a line in the spectrum, known as an absorption line, which corresponds to the energy difference between states 1 and 2.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The atomic orbital model thus predicts line spectra, which are observed experimentally.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] This is one of the main validations of the atomic orbital model.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The atomic orbital model is nevertheless an approximation to the full quantum theory, which only recognizes many electron states.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-orbital-p02] The predictions of line spectra are qualitatively useful but are not quantitatively accurate for atoms and ions other than those containing only one electron.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The term *atomic physics* can be associated with nuclear power and nuclear weapons, due to the synonymous use of *atomic* and *nuclear* in standard English.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Physicists distinguish between atomic physics—which deals with the atom as a system consisting of a nucleus and electrons—and nuclear physics, which studies nuclear reactions and special properties of atomic nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] As with many scientific fields, strict delineation can be highly contrived and atomic physics is often considered in the wider context of atomic, molecular, and optical physics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] As a result, atomic physics research groups are usually classified as such.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Atomic physics primarily considers atoms in isolation.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Atomic models will consist of a single nucleus that may be surrounded by one or more bound electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] It is not concerned with the formation of molecules (although much of the physics is identical), nor does it examine atoms in a solid state as condensed matter.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] It is concerned with processes such as ionization and excitation by photons or collisions with atomic particles.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] While modelling atoms in isolation may not seem realistic, if one considers atoms in a gas or plasma then the time-scales for atom-atom interactions are huge in comparison to the atomic processes that are generally considered.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] This means that the individual atoms can be treated as if each were in isolation, as the vast majority of the time they are.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] By this consideration, atomic physics provides the underlying theory in plasma physics and atmospheric physics, even though both deal with very large numbers of atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Electrons form notional shells around the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] These are normally in a ground state but can be excited by the absorption of energy from light (photons), magnetic fields, or interaction with a colliding particle (typically ions or other electrons).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Electrons that populate a shell are said to be in a bound state.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The energy necessary to remove an electron from its shell (taking it to infinity) is called the binding energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Any quantity of energy absorbed by the electron in excess of this amount is converted to kinetic energy according to the conservation of energy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The atom is said to have undergone the process of ionization.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] If the electron absorbs a quantity of energy less than the binding energy, it will be transferred to an excited state.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] After a certain time, the electron in an excited state will "jump" (undergo a transition) to a lower state.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] In a neutral atom, the system will emit a photon of the difference in energy, since energy is conserved.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] If an inner electron has absorbed more than the binding energy (so that the atom ionizes), then a more outer electron may undergo a transition to fill the inner orbital.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] In this case, a visible photon or a characteristic X-ray is emitted, or a phenomenon known as the Auger effect may take place, where the released energy is transferred to another bound electron, causing it to go into the continuum.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The Auger effect allows one to multiply ionize an atom with a single photon.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] There are rather strict selection rules as to the electronic configurations that can be reached by excitation by light –however, there are no such rules for excitation by collision processes.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The Bohr model, proposed by **Niels Bohr in 1913**, is a revolutionary theory describing the structure of the hydrogen atom.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] It introduced the idea of quantized orbits for electrons, combining classical and quantum physics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] One of the earliest steps towards atomic physics was the recognition that matter was composed of *atoms*.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] It forms a part of the texts written in 6th century BC to 2nd century BC, such as those of Democritus or **Vaiśeṣika Sūtra** written by Kaṇāda.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] This theory was later developed in the modern sense of the basic unit of a chemical element by the British chemist and physicist John Dalton in the 18th century.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] At this stage, it was not clear what atoms were, although they could be described and classified by their properties (in bulk).
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The invention of the periodic system of elements by Dmitri Mendeleev was another great step forward.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The true beginning of atomic physics is marked by the discovery of spectral lines and attempts to describe the phenomenon, most notably by Joseph von Fraunhofer.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] The study of these lines led to the Bohr atom model and to the birth of quantum mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] In seeking to explain atomic spectra, an entirely new mathematical model of matter was revealed.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] As far as atoms and their electron shells were concerned, not only did this yield a better overall description, i.e. the atomic orbital model, but it also provided a new theoretical basis for chemistry (quantum chemistry) and spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Since the Second World War, both theoretical and experimental fields have advanced at a rapid pace.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] This can be attributed to progress in computing technology, which has allowed larger and more sophisticated models of atomic structure and associated collision processes.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Similar technological advances in accelerators, detectors, magnetic field generation and lasers have greatly assisted experimental work.
[src:atomic-physics/atomic-physics] Beyond the well-known phenomena which can be described with regular quantum mechanics chaotic processes can occur which need different descriptions.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In atomic physics, the **Bohr model** or **Rutherford–Bohr model** is an obsolete model of the atom that incorporated some early quantum concepts.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Developed from 1911 to 1918 by Niels Bohr and building on Ernest Rutherford's discovery of the atom's nucleus, it supplanted the plum pudding model of J.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thomson only to be replaced by the quantum atomic model in the 1920s.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] It consists of a small, dense atomic nucleus surrounded by orbiting electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] It is analogous to the structure of the Solar System, but with attraction provided by electrostatic force rather than gravity, and with the electron energies quantized (assuming only discrete values).
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The improvement over the 1911 Rutherford model mainly concerned the new quantum mechanical interpretation introduced by Haas and Nicholson, but forsaking any attempt to explain radiation according to classical physics.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The model's key success lies in explaining the Rydberg formula for hydrogen's spectral emission lines.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] While the Rydberg formula had been known experimentally, it did not gain a theoretical basis until the Bohr model was introduced.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Not only did the Bohr model explain the reasons for the structure of the Rydberg formula, it also provided a justification for the fundamental physical constants that make up the formula's empirical results.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Bohr model is a relatively primitive model of the hydrogen atom, compared to the valence shell model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] As a theory, it can be derived as a first-order approximation of the hydrogen atom using the broader and much more accurate quantum mechanics and thus may be considered to be an obsolete scientific theory.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] However, because of its simplicity, and its correct results for selected systems (see below for application), the Bohr model is still commonly taught to introduce students to quantum mechanics or energy level diagrams before moving on to the more accurate, but more complex, valence shell atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] A related quantum model was proposed by Arthur Erich Haas in 1910 but was rejected until the 1911 Solvay Congress where it was thoroughly discussed.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The quantum theory of the period between Planck's discovery of the quantum (1900) and the advent of a mature quantum mechanics (1925) is often referred to as the *old quantum theory*.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Until the second decade of the 20th century, atomic models were generally speculative.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Even the concept of atoms, let alone atoms with internal structure, faced opposition from some scientists.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In the late 1800s speculations on the possible structure of the atom included planetary models with orbiting charged electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] These models faced a significant constraint.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1897, Joseph Larmor showed that an accelerating charge would radiate power according to classical electrodynamics, a result known as the Larmor formula.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Since electrons forced to remain in orbit are continuously accelerating, they would be mechanically unstable.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Larmor noted that electromagnetic effect of multiple electrons, suitably arranged, would cancel each other.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thus subsequent atomic models based on classical electrodynamics needed to adopt such special multi-electron arrangements.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] When Bohr began his work on a new atomic theory in the summer of 1912 the atomic model proposed by J.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thomson, now known as the plum pudding model, was the best available.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thomson proposed a model with electrons rotating in coplanar rings within an atomic-sized, positively-charged, spherical volume.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thomson showed that this model was mechanically stable by lengthy calculations and was electrodynamically stable under his original assumption of thousands of electrons per atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Moreover, he suggested that the particularly stable configurations of electrons in rings was connected to chemical properties of the atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] He developed a formula for the scattering of beta particles that seemed to match experimental results.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] However Thomson himself later showed that the atom had a factor of a thousand fewer electrons, challenging the stability argument and forcing the poorly understood positive sphere to have most of the atom's mass.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thomson was also unable to explain the many lines in atomic spectra.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1908, Hans Geiger and Ernest Marsden demonstrated that alpha particles occasionally scatter at large angles, a result inconsistent with Thomson's model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1911 Ernest Rutherford developed a new scattering model, showing that the observed large angle scattering could be explained by a compact, highly charged mass at the center of the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Rutherford scattering did not involve the electrons and thus his model of the atom was incomplete.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr begins his first paper on his atomic model by describing Rutherford's atom as consisting of a small, dense, positively charged nucleus attracting negatively charged electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] By the early twentieth century, it was expected that a successful model of the atom should account for the many atomic spectral lines.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] These lines were summarized in empirical formulas by Johann Balmer and Johannes Rydberg.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1897, Lord Rayleigh showed that vibrations of electrical systems predicted spectral lines that depend on the square of the vibrational frequency, contradicting the empirical formula which depended directly on the frequency.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Conway showed that, rather than the entire atom vibrating, vibrations of only one of the electrons in the system described by Thomson might be sufficient to account for spectral series.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Although Bohr's model would also rely on just the electron to explain the spectrum, he did not assume an electrodynamical model for the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The other important advance in the understanding of atomic spectra was the Rydberg–Ritz combination principle which related atomic spectral line frequencies to differences between 'terms', special frequencies characteristic of each element.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr would recognize the terms as energy levels of the atom divided by the Planck constant, leading to the modern view that the spectral lines result from energy differences.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1910, Arthur Erich Haas proposed a model of the hydrogen atom with an electron circulating on the surface of a sphere of positive charge.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Haas combined this constraint with the balance-of-forces equation.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The attractive force between the electron and the sphere balances the centrifugal force: ${\frac {e^{2}}{a^{2}}}=ma(2\pi f)^{2}$ where m is the mass of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This combination relates the radius of the sphere to the Planck constant: $a={\frac {h^{2}}{4\pi ^{2}e^{2}m}}$ Haas solved for the Planck constant using the then-current value for the radius of the hydrogen atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Three years later, Bohr would use similar equations with different interpretation.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr took the Planck constant as a given value and used the equations to predict a, the radius of the electron orbiting in the ground state of the hydrogen atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This value is now called the Bohr radius.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The first Solvay Conference, in 1911, was one of the first international physics conferences.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Nine Nobel or future Nobel laureates attended, including Ernest Rutherford, Bohr's mentor.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr did not attend but he read the Solvay reports and discussed them with Rutherford.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The subject of the conference was the theory of radiation and the energy quanta of Max Planck's oscillators.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Planck's lecture at the conference ended with comments about atoms and the discussion that followed it concerned atomic models.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Hendrik Lorentz raised the question of the composition of the atom based on Haas's model, a form of Thomson's plum pudding model with a quantum modification.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Lorentz explained that the size of atoms could be taken to determine the Planck constant as Haas had done or the Planck constant could be taken as determining the size of atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The discussions outlined the need for the quantum theory to be included in the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Planck explicitly mentions the failings of classical mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] While Bohr had already expressed a similar opinion in his PhD thesis, at Solvay the leading scientists of the day discussed a break with classical theories.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1911 John William Nicholson published a model of the atom which would influence Bohr's model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Nicholson developed his model based on the analysis of astrophysical spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] He connected the observed spectral line frequencies with the orbits of electrons in his atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The connection he adopted associated the atomic electron orbital angular momentum with the Planck constant.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Whereas Planck focused on a quantum of energy, Nicholson's angular momentum quantum relates to orbital frequency.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This new concept gave Planck constant an atomic meaning for the first time.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In his 1913 paper Bohr cites Nicholson as finding quantized angular momentum important for the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The other critical influence of Nicholson work was his detailed analysis of spectra.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Before Nicholson's work Bohr thought the spectral data was not useful for understanding atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In comparing his work to Nicholson's, Bohr came to understand the spectral data and their value.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] When he then learned from a friend about Balmer's compact formula for the spectral line data, Bohr quickly realized his model would match it in detail.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Nicholson's model was based on classical electrodynamics along the lines of J.J.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Thomson's plum pudding model but his negative electrons orbiting a positive nucleus rather than circulating in a sphere.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] To avoid immediate collapse of this system he required that electrons come in pairs so the rotational acceleration of each electron was matched across the orbit.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] By 1913 Bohr had already shown, from the analysis of alpha particle energy loss, that hydrogen had only a single electron not a matched pair.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr's atomic model would abandon classical electrodynamics.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Nicholson's model of radiation was quantum but was attached to the orbits of the electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr quantization would associate it with differences in energy levels of his model of hydrogen rather than the orbital frequency.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr completed his PhD in 1911 with a thesis 'Studies on the Electron Theory of Metals', an application of the classical electron theory of Hendrik Lorentz.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr noted two deficits of the classical model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The first concerned the specific heat of metals which James Clerk Maxwell noted in 1875: every additional degree of freedom in a theory of metals, like subatomic electrons, cause more disagreement with experiment.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The second, the classical theory could not explain magnetism.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] After his PhD, Bohr worked briefly in the lab of JJ Thomson before moving to Rutherford's lab in Manchester to study radioactivity.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] He arrived just after Rutherford completed his proposal of a compact nuclear core for atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Charles Galton Darwin, also at Manchester, had just completed an analysis of alpha particle energy loss in metals, concluding the electron collisions were the dominant cause of loss.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr showed in a subsequent paper that Darwin's results would improve by accounting for electron binding energy.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Importantly this allowed Bohr to conclude that hydrogen atoms have a single electron.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Next, Bohr was told by his friend, Hans Hansen, that the Balmer series is calculated using the Balmer formula, an empirical equation discovered by Johann Balmer in 1885 that described wavelengths of some spectral lines of hydrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This was further generalized by Johannes Rydberg in 1888, resulting in what is now known as the Rydberg formula.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] After this, Bohr declared, "everything became clear".
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The electrons otherwise obey ordinary mechanics in the stationary orbits.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The absorption or emission of electromagnetic radiation with a frequency $\nu$ is related to an energy according to the Planck relation: $E=h\nu$ , where h is the Planck constant.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The stationary orbits are obtained by the condition that the ratio of the total energy emitted in forming the state and the frequency of the electron rotation about the positive nucleus is an integer multiple of $h/2$ .
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In atomic state corresponding to the maximum emitted energy, the stationary orbits are attained at distances for which the angular momentum of the revolving electron is equal to the reduced Planck constant, $h/2\pi$ .
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The first two postulates formulate the experimental observations that absorption and emission of radiation for hydrogen do not obey the rules known at the time.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The third postulate restates Planck's quantum theory of radiation which was already widely accepted by 1913.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The fourth and fifth postulates are combined in modern discussions.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In the combined form the stationary orbits are given by $m_{\mathrm {e} }vr=n\hbar$ , where $n=1,2,3,...$ is called the principal quantum number, and $\hbar =h/2\pi$ .
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The lowest value of n is 1; this gives the smallest possible orbital radius, known as the Bohr radius, of 0.0529 nm for hydrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Once an electron is in this lowest orbit, it can get no closer to the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr's condition, that the angular momentum be an integer multiple of $\hbar ,$ was later reinterpreted in 1924 by de Broglie as a standing wave condition.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] According to de Broglie's hypothesis, matter particles such as the electron behave as waves.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] where $mvr$ is the angular momentum of the orbiting electron.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] which is the combined form of Bohr's fourth and fifth postulate.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1932, these two postulates where further justified when C.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Raman and Suri Bhagavantam experimentally demonstrated that a photon carries an angular momentum of $\hbar$ .
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr had assumed that electrons can transition between stationary orbits, during which a photon is either absorbed or emitted by the system.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] With the measurement of the photon angular momentum, the law of conservation of angular momentum predicts that the angular momentum of an electron on a stationary orbit must equal an integer multiple of $\hbar$ .
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Starting from the angular momentum quantum rule as Bohr admits is previously given by Nicholson in his 1912 paper, Bohr was able to calculate the energies of the allowed orbits of the hydrogen atom and other hydrogen-like atoms and ions.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] These orbits are associated with definite energies and are also called energy shells or energy levels.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In these orbits, the electron's acceleration does not result in radiation and energy loss.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Several enhancements to the Bohr model were proposed, most notably the Sommerfeld or Bohr–Sommerfeld models, which suggested that electrons travel in elliptical orbits around a nucleus instead of the Bohr model's circular orbits.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] where *p*r is the radial momentum canonically conjugate to the coordinate *q*r, which is the radial position, and *T* is one full orbital period.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The integral is the action of action-angle coordinates.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This condition, suggested by the correspondence principle, is the only one possible, since the quantum numbers are adiabatic invariants.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Bohr–Sommerfeld model was fundamentally inconsistent and led to many paradoxes.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The magnetic quantum number measured the tilt of the orbital plane relative to the *xy* plane, and it could only take a few discrete values.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This contradicted the obvious fact that an atom could have any orientation relative to the coordinates, without restriction.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Sommerfeld quantization can be performed in different canonical coordinates and sometimes gives different answers.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The incorporation of radiation corrections was difficult, because it required finding action-angle coordinates for a combined radiation/atom system, which is difficult when the radiation is allowed to escape.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The whole theory did not extend to non-integrable motions, which meant that many systems could not be treated even in principle.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In the end, the model was replaced by the modern quantum-mechanical treatment of the hydrogen atom, which was first given by Wolfgang Pauli in 1925, using Heisenberg's matrix mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The current picture of the hydrogen atom is based on the atomic orbitals of wave mechanics, which Erwin Schrödinger developed in 1926.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] However, this is not to say that the Bohr–Sommerfeld model was without its successes.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Calculations based on the Bohr–Sommerfeld model were able to accurately explain a number of more complex atomic spectral effects.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] For example, up to first-order perturbations, the Bohr model and quantum mechanics make the same predictions for the spectral line splitting in the Stark effect.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] At higher-order perturbations, however, the Bohr model and quantum mechanics differ, and measurements of the Stark effect under high field strengths helped confirm the correctness of quantum mechanics over the Bohr model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The prevailing theory behind this difference lies in the shapes of the orbitals of the electrons, which vary according to the energy state of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Bohr–Sommerfeld quantization conditions lead to questions in modern mathematics.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Consistent semiclassical quantization condition requires a certain type of structure on the phase space, which places topological limitations on the types of symplectic manifolds which can be quantized.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In particular, the symplectic form should be the curvature form of a connection of a Hermitian line bundle, which is called a prequantization.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr also updated his model in 1922, assuming that certain numbers of electrons (for example, 2, 8, and 18) correspond to stable "closed shells".
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1925, a new kind of mechanics was proposed, quantum mechanics, in which Bohr's model of electrons traveling in quantized orbits was extended into more accurate model of electron motion.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The new framework of the theory was proposed by Werner Heisenberg in the Umdeutung paper that was later extended into matrix mechanics with Max Born and Pascual Jordan.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Another form of the same theory, wave mechanics, was discovered by the Austrian physicist Erwin Schrödinger independently, and by different reasoning.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Schrödinger employed de Broglie's matter waves, but sought wave solutions of a three-dimensional wave equation describing electrons that were constrained to move about the nucleus of a hydrogen-like atom, by being trapped by the potential of the positive nuclear charge.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Bohr model gives almost exact results only for a system where two charged points orbit each other at speeds much less than that of light.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This not only involves one-electron systems such as the hydrogen atom, singly ionized helium, and doubly ionized lithium, but it includes positronium and Rydberg states of any atom where one electron is far away from everything else.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] It can be used for K-line X-ray transition calculations if other assumptions are added (see Moseley's law below).
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In high energy physics, it can be used to calculate the masses of heavy quark mesons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Calculation of the orbits requires two assumptions.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] However, in quantum mechanics, the quantization of angular momentum leads to discrete energy levels of the orbits, and the emitted frequencies are quantized according to the energy differences between these levels.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This discrete nature of energy levels introduces a fundamental departure from the classical radiation law, giving rise to distinct spectral lines in the emitted radiation.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr assumes that the electron is circling the nucleus in an elliptical orbit obeying the rules of classical mechanics, but with no loss of radiation due to the Larmor formula.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] (1b) is obtained from the same premises of eq.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] (4) stems from the virial theorem, and from the classical mechanics relationships between the angular momentum, the kinetic energy and the frequency of revolution.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This results states that the angular momentum of the electron is an integer multiple of the reduced Planck constant.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] An electron in the lowest energy level of hydrogen (*n* = 1) therefore has about 13.6 eV less energy than a motionless electron infinitely far from the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The next energy level (*n* = 2) is −3.4 eV.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] For larger values of *n*, these are also the binding energies of a highly excited atom with one electron in a large circular orbit around the rest of the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The hydrogen formula also coincides with the Wallis product.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Since this derivation is with the assumption that the nucleus is orbited by one electron, we can generalize this result by letting the nucleus have a charge *q* = *Ze*, where *Z* is the atomic number.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This will now give us energy levels for hydrogenic (hydrogen-like) atoms, which can serve as a rough order-of-magnitude approximation of the actual energy levels.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The actual energy levels cannot be solved analytically for more than one electron (see *n*-body problem) because the electrons are not only affected by the nucleus but also interact with each other via the Coulomb force.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] When *Z* = 1/*α* (*Z* ≈ 137), the motion becomes highly relativistic, and *Z*2 cancels the *α*2 in *R*; the orbit energy begins to be comparable to rest energy.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Sufficiently large nuclei, if they were stable, would reduce their charge by creating a bound electron from the vacuum, ejecting the positron to infinity.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This is the theoretical phenomenon of electromagnetic charge screening which predicts a maximum nuclear charge.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Emission of such positrons has been observed in the collisions of heavy ions to create temporary super-heavy nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] However, these numbers are very nearly the same, due to the much larger mass of the proton, about 1836.1 times the mass of the electron, so that the reduced mass in the system is the mass of the electron multiplied by the constant 1836.1/(1 + 1836.1) = 0.99946.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] For positronium, the formula uses the reduced mass also, but in this case, it is exactly the electron mass divided by 2.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] For any value of the radius, the electron and the positron are each moving at half the speed around their common center of mass, and each has only one fourth the kinetic energy.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The total kinetic energy is half what it would be for a single electron moving around a heavy nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Beginning in late 1860s, Johann Balmer and later Johannes Rydberg and Walther Ritz developed increasingly accurate empirical formula matching measured atomic spectral lines.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Critical for Bohr's later work, Rydberg expressed his formula in terms of wave-number, equivalent to frequency.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] These formulae contained a constant, R , now known the Rydberg constant and a pair of integers indexing the lines: $\nu =R\left({\frac {1}{m^{2}}}-{\frac {1}{n^{2}}}\right).$ Despite many attempts, no theory of the atom could reproduce these relatively simple formulae.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In Bohr's theory, describing the energies of transitions or quantum jumps between orbital energy levels can explain the Rydberg formula.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This was established empirically before Bohr presented his model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr's original three papers in 1913 described mainly the electron configuration in lighter elements.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr called his electron shells, "rings" in 1913.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Atomic orbitals within shells did not exist at the time of his planetary model.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] However, in larger atoms the innermost shell would contain eight electrons, "on the other hand, the periodic system of the elements strongly suggests that already in neon *N* = 10 an inner ring of eight electrons will occur".
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In Bohr's third 1913 paper Part III called "Systems Containing Several Nuclei", he says that two atoms form molecules on a symmetrical plane and he reverts to describing hydrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The 1913 Bohr model did not discuss higher elements in detail and John William Nicholson was one of the first to prove in 1914 that it couldn't work for lithium, but was an attractive theory for hydrogen and ionized helium.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1921, following the work of chemists and others involved in work on the periodic table, Bohr extended the model of hydrogen to give an approximate model for heavier atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr's partner in research during 1914 to 1916 was Walther Kossel who corrected Bohr's work to show that electrons interacted through the outer rings, and Kossel called the rings: "shells".
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Irving Langmuir is credited with the first viable arrangement of electrons in shells with only two in the first shell and going up to eight in the next according to the octet rule of 1904, although Kossel had already predicted a maximum of eight per shell in 1916.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Heavier atoms have more protons in the nucleus, and more electrons to cancel the charge.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Bohr took from these chemists the idea that each discrete orbit could only hold a certain number of electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Per Kossel, after that the orbit is full, the next level would have to be used.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This gives the atom a shell structure designed by Kossel, Langmuir, and Bury, in which each shell corresponds to a Bohr orbit.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This model is even more approximate than the model of hydrogen, because it treats the electrons in each shell as non-interacting.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] But the repulsions of electrons are taken into account somewhat by the phenomenon of screening.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The electrons in outer orbits do not only orbit the nucleus, but they also move around the inner electrons, so the effective charge Z that they feel is reduced by the number of the electrons in the inner orbit.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] For example, the lithium atom has two electrons in the lowest 1s orbit, and these orbit at *Z* = 2.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Each one sees the nuclear charge of *Z* = 3 minus the screening effect of the other, which crudely reduces the nuclear charge by 1 unit.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This means that the innermost electrons orbit at approximately 1/2 the Bohr radius.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The outermost electron in lithium orbits at roughly the Bohr radius, since the two inner electrons reduce the nuclear charge by 2.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This outer electron should be at nearly one Bohr radius from the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Because the electrons strongly repel each other, the effective charge description is very approximate; the effective charge *Z* doesn't usually come out to be an integer.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The shell model was able to qualitatively explain many of the mysterious properties of atoms which became codified in the late 19th century in the periodic table of the elements.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] One property was the size of atoms, which could be determined approximately by measuring the viscosity of gases and density of pure crystalline solids.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Atoms tend to get smaller toward the right in the periodic table, and become much larger at the next line of the table.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Atoms to the right of the table tend to gain electrons, while atoms to the left tend to lose them.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Every element on the last column of the table is chemically inert (noble gas).
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In the shell model, this phenomenon is explained by shell-filling.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Successive atoms become smaller because they are filling orbits of the same size, until the orbit is full, at which point the next atom in the table has a loosely bound outer electron, causing it to expand.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The first Bohr orbit is filled when it has two electrons, which explains why helium is inert.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The second orbit allows eight electrons, and when it is full the atom is neon, again inert.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The third orbital contains eight again, except that in the more correct Sommerfeld treatment (reproduced in modern quantum mechanics) there are extra "d" electrons.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The third orbit may hold an extra 10 d electrons, but these positions are not filled until a few more orbitals from the next level are filled (filling the *n* = 3 d-orbitals produces the 10 transition elements).
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The irregular filling pattern is an effect of interactions between electrons, which are not taken into account in either the Bohr or Sommerfeld models and which are difficult to calculate even in the modern treatment.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Niels Bohr said in 1962: "You see actually the Rutherford work was not taken seriously.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] We cannot understand today, but it was not taken seriously at all.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In 1913, Henry Moseley found an empirical relationship between the strongest X-ray line emitted by atoms under electron bombardment (then known as the K-alpha line), and their atomic number *Z*.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The two additional assumptions that **[1]** this X-ray line came from a transition between energy levels with quantum numbers 1 and 2, and **[2]**, that the atomic number *Z* when used in the formula for atoms heavier than hydrogen, should be diminished by 1, to (*Z* − 1)2.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Moseley wrote to Bohr, puzzled about his results, but Bohr was not able to help.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] At that time, he thought that the postulated innermost "K" shell of electrons should have at least four electrons, not the two which would have neatly explained the result.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] So Moseley published his results without a theoretical explanation.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] It was Walther Kossel in 1914 and in 1916 who explained that in the periodic table new elements would be created as electrons were added to the outer shell.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In Kossel's paper, he writes: "This leads to the conclusion that the electrons, which are added further, should be put into concentric rings or shells, on each of which ... only a certain number of electrons—namely, eight in our case—should be arranged.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In his 1919 paper, Irving Langmuir postulated the existence of "cells" which could each only contain two electrons each, and these were arranged in "equidistant layers".
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In the Moseley experiment, one of the innermost electrons in the atom is knocked out, leaving a vacancy in the lowest Bohr orbit, which contains a single remaining electron.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This vacancy is then filled by an electron from the next orbit, which has n=2.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] For values of *Z* between 11 and 31 this latter relationship had been empirically derived by Moseley, in a simple (linear) plot of the square root of X-ray frequency against atomic number (however, for silver, Z = 47, the experimentally obtained screening term should be replaced by 0.4).
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Van den Broek had published his model in January 1913 showing the periodic table was arranged according to charge while Bohr's atomic model was not published until July 1913.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The K-alpha line of Moseley's time is now known to be a pair of close lines, written as (**Kα1** and **Kα2**) in Siegbahn notation.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Bohr model gives an incorrect value *L*=*ħ* for the ground state orbital angular momentum: The angular momentum in the true ground state is known to be zero from experiment.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] This is only reproduced in a more sophisticated semiclassical treatment like Sommerfeld's.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Still, even the most sophisticated semiclassical model fails to explain the fact that the lowest energy state is spherically symmetric – it does not point in any particular direction.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] In modern quantum mechanics, the electron in hydrogen is a spherical cloud of probability that grows denser near the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The rate-constant of probability-decay in hydrogen is equal to the inverse of the Bohr radius, but since Bohr worked with circular orbits, not zero area ellipses, the fact that these two numbers exactly agree is considered a "coincidence".
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Another issue with the Bohr model was that although an electron in a stationary state n is described in periodic motion, and therefore should be associated with a characteristic radiation frequency $\omega (n)$ , no such frequency was experimentally measured.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Heisenberg attempted to fix this issue in the Umdeutung paper by replacing the idea of a single orbital frequency associated with the electron's motion by the set of observable spectral frequencies $\omega (n,n-\alpha )$ (for a quantum transition from stationary state n to $n-\alpha$ ).
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] By this time, however, the electronic orbit was practically abandoned as physically meaningful.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Niels Bohr proposed a model of the atom and a model of the chemical bond.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] According to his model for a diatomic molecule, the electrons of the atoms of the molecule form a rotating ring whose plane is perpendicular to the axis of the molecule and equidistant from the atomic nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The dynamic equilibrium of the molecular system is achieved through the balance of forces between the forces of attraction of nuclei to the plane of the ring of electrons and the forces of mutual repulsion of the nuclei.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The Bohr model of the chemical bond took into account the Coulomb repulsion – the electrons in the ring are at the maximum distance from each other.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] Although Bohr's atomic model was superseded by quantum models in the 1920s, the visual image of electrons orbiting a nucleus has remained the popular concept of atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/bohr-model] The concept of an atom as a tiny planetary system has been widely used as a symbol for atoms and even for "atomic" energy (even though this is more properly considered nuclear energy).
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] In atomic physics, the **fine structure** describes the splitting of the spectral lines of atoms due to electron spin and relativistic corrections to the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] It was first measured precisely for the hydrogen atom by Albert A.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The explanation was first given by Niels Bohr in 1914, who suggested that the orbits of electrons in his Bohr model of the atom precessed due to relativistic effects.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] A successful relativistic formula was given by Arnold Sommerfeld in 1916.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] In the same work, Sommerfeld also introduced the fine-structure constant.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The *gross structure* of line spectra is the structure predicted by the quantum mechanics of non-relativistic electrons with no spin.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] For a hydrogenic atom, the gross structure energy levels only depend on the principal quantum number *n*.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] However, a more accurate model takes into account relativistic and spin effects, which break the degeneracy of the energy levels and split the spectral lines.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The scale of the fine structure splitting relative to the gross structure energies is on the order of (*Zα*)2, where *Z* is the atomic number and *α* is the fine-structure constant, a dimensionless number equal to approximately 1/137.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The fine structure energy corrections can be obtained by using perturbation theory.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] To perform this calculation one must add three corrective terms to the Hamiltonian: the leading order relativistic correction to the kinetic energy, the correction due to the spin–orbit coupling, and the Darwin term coming from the quantum fluctuating motion or zitterbewegung of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] These corrections can also be obtained from the non-relativistic limit of the Dirac equation, since Dirac's theory naturally incorporates relativity and spin interactions.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] This section discusses the analytical solutions for the hydrogen atom as the problem is analytically solvable and is the base model for energy level calculations in more complex atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] To further simplify, we note that the term under the square root can be written of the form $(1+x)^{p}$ where the value of x satisfies the conditions to approximate the entire square root term as the first two terms of its Taylor series expansion.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] Although there are an infinite number of terms in this series, the later terms are much smaller than earlier terms, and so we can ignore all but the first two.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] On final calculation, the relativistic correction to the ground state is −9.056×10−4 eV.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The spin–orbit correction can be understood by shifting from the standard frame of reference (where the electron orbits the nucleus) into one where the electron is stationary and the nucleus instead orbits it.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] In this case the orbiting nucleus functions as an effective current loop, which in turn will generate a magnetic field.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] However, the electron itself has a magnetic moment due to its intrinsic angular momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The two magnetic vectors, $\mathbf {B}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\mu }}_{s}$ couple together so that there is a certain energy cost depending on their relative orientation.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] Notice that an important factor of 2 has to be added to the calculation, called the Thomas precession, which comes from the relativistic calculation that changes back to the electron's frame from the nucleus frame.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] When weak external magnetic fields are applied, the spin–orbit coupling contributes to the Zeeman effect.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] There is one last term in the non-relativistic expansion of the Dirac equation.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The Darwin term affects only the s orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] This is because the wave function of an electron with $\ell >0$ vanishes at the origin, hence the delta function has no effect.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] For example, it gives the 2s orbital the same energy as the 2p orbital by raising the 2s state by 9.057×10−5 eV.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The Darwin term changes potential energy of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] It can be interpreted as a smearing out of the electrostatic interaction between the electron and nucleus due to zitterbewegung, or rapid quantum oscillations, of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] This can be demonstrated by a short calculation.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] Quantum fluctuations allow for the creation of virtual electron–positron pairs with a lifetime estimated by the uncertainty principle $\Delta t\approx \hbar /\Delta E\approx \hbar /mc^{2}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The distance the particles can move during this time is $\xi \approx c\Delta t\approx \hbar /mc=\lambda \!\!\!{\bar {}}_{\text{C}}$ , their reduced Compton wavelength.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The electrons of the atom interact with those pairs.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] This yields a fluctuating electron position $\mathbf {r} +{\boldsymbol {\xi }}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] Another mechanism that affects only the s-state is the Lamb shift, a further, smaller correction that arises in quantum electrodynamics that should not be confused with the Darwin term.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The Darwin term gives the s-state and p-state the same energy, but the Lamb shift makes the s-state higher in energy than the p-state.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The full Hamiltonian is given by ${\mathcal {H}}={\mathcal {H}}_{\text{Coulomb}}+{\mathcal {H}}_{\text{kinetic}}+{\mathcal {H}}_{\mathrm {SO} }+{\mathcal {H}}_{\text{Darwin}},$ where ${\mathcal {H}}_{\text{Coulomb}}$ is the Hamiltonian from the Coulomb interaction.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] It is worth noting that this expression was first obtained by Sommerfeld based on the old quantum theory; i.e., before modern quantum mechanics was reformulated by Werner Heisenberg and Erwin Schrödinger.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] The total effect can also be obtained by using the Dirac equation.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] This expression, which contains all higher order terms that were left out in the other calculations, expands to first order to give the energy corrections derived from perturbation theory.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] However, this equation does not contain the hyperfine structure corrections, which are due to interactions with the nuclear spin.
[src:atomic-physics/fine-structure] Other corrections from quantum field theory such as the Lamb shift and the anomalous magnetic dipole moment of the electron are not included.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In atomic physics, **hyperfine structure** is defined by small shifts in otherwise degenerate electronic energy levels and the resulting splittings in those electronic energy levels of atoms, molecules, and ions, due to electromagnetic multipole interaction between the nucleus and electron clouds.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In atoms, hyperfine structure arises from the energy of the nuclear magnetic dipole moment interacting with the magnetic field generated by the electrons and the energy of the nuclear electric quadrupole moment in the electric field gradient due to the distribution of charge within the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Hyperfine structure contrasts with *fine structure*, which results from the interaction between the magnetic moments associated with electron spin and the electrons' orbital angular momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Hyperfine structure, with energy shifts typically orders of magnitude smaller than those of a fine-structure shift, results from the interactions of the nucleus (or nuclei, in molecules) with internally generated electric and magnetic fields.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The first theory of atomic hyperfine structure was given in 1930 by Enrico Fermi for an atom containing a single valence electron with an arbitrary angular momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The Zeeman splitting of this structure was discussed by S.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Schüler and Theodor Schmidt proposed the existence of a nuclear quadrupole moment in order to explain anomalies in the hyperfine structure of europium, cassiopium (older name for lutetium), indium, antimony, and mercury.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The theory of hyperfine structure comes directly from electromagnetism, consisting of the interaction of the nuclear multipole moments (excluding the electric monopole) with internally generated fields.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The theory is derived first for the atomic case, but can be applied to *each nucleus* in a molecule.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Following this there is a discussion of the additional effects unique to the molecular case.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The dominant term in the hyperfine Hamiltonian is typically the magnetic dipole term.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Atomic nuclei with a non-zero nuclear spin $\mathbf {I}$ have a magnetic dipole moment, given by: ${\boldsymbol {\mu }}_{\text{I}}=g_{\text{I}}\mu _{\text{N}}\mathbf {I} ,$ where $g_{\text{I}}$ is the *g*-factor and $\mu _{\text{N}}$ is the nuclear magneton.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] There is an energy associated with a magnetic dipole moment in the presence of a magnetic field.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Electron orbital angular momentum results from the motion of the electron about some fixed external point that we shall take to be the location of the nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The electron spin angular momentum is a fundamentally different property that is intrinsic to the particle and therefore does not depend on the motion of the electron.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Nonetheless, it is angular momentum and any angular momentum associated with a charged particle results in a magnetic dipole moment, which is the source of a magnetic field.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The first term gives the energy of the nuclear dipole in the field due to the electronic orbital angular momentum.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The second term gives the energy of the "finite distance" interaction of the nuclear dipole with the field due to the electron spin magnetic moments.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The final term, often known as the *Fermi contact* term relates to the direct interaction of the nuclear dipole with the spin dipoles and is only non-zero for states with a finite electron spin density at the position of the nucleus (those with unpaired electrons in *s*-subshells).
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] It has been argued that one may get a different expression when taking into account the detailed nuclear magnetic moment distribution.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The inclusion of the delta function is an admission that the singularity in the magnetic induction **B** owing to a magnetic dipole moment at a point is not integrable.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] It is **B** which mediates the interaction between the Pauli spinors in non-relativistic quantum mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Fermi (1930) avoided the difficulty by working with the relativistic Dirac wave equation, according to which the mediating field for the Dirac spinors is the four-vector potential (V,**A**).
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The component V is the Coulomb potential.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The component **A** is the three-vector magnetic potential (such that **B** = **curl A**), which for the point dipole is integrable.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] If hyperfine structure is small compared with the fine structure (sometimes called *IJ*-coupling by analogy with *LS*-coupling), *I* and *J* are good quantum numbers and matrix elements of ${\hat {H}}_{\text{D}}$ can be approximated as diagonal in *I* and *J*.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] This is commonly written as ${\hat {H}}_{\text{D}}={\hat {A}}\mathbf {I} \cdot \mathbf {J} ,$ with ${\textstyle \left\langle {\hat {A}}\right\rangle }$ being the hyperfine-structure constant which is determined by experiment.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In this case the hyperfine interaction satisfies the Landé interval rule.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Atomic nuclei with spin $I\geq 1$ have an electric quadrupole moment.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Being a 3-dimensional rank-2 tensor, the quadrupole moment has 32 = 9 components.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] From the definition of the components it is clear that the quadrupole tensor is a symmetric matrix (*Qij* = *Qji*) that is also traceless ( ${\textstyle \operatorname {tr} Q=\sum _{i}Q_{ii}=0}$ ), giving only five components in the irreducible representation.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] A typical atomic nucleus closely approximates cylindrical symmetry and therefore all off-diagonal elements are close to zero.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] For this reason the nuclear electric quadrupole moment is often represented by *Q**zz*.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The molecular hyperfine Hamiltonian includes those terms already derived for the atomic case with a magnetic dipole term for each nucleus with $I>0$ and an electric quadrupole term for each nucleus with $I\geq 1$ .
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The magnetic dipole terms were first derived for diatomic molecules by Frosch and Foley, and the resulting hyperfine parameters are often called the Frosch and Foley parameters.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In addition to the effects described above, there are a number of effects specific to the molecular case.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Each nucleus with $I>0$ has a non-zero magnetic moment that is both the source of a magnetic field and has an associated energy due to the presence of the combined field of all of the other nuclear magnetic moments.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] A typical simple example of the hyperfine structure due to the interactions discussed above is in the rotational transitions of hydrogen cyanide (1H12C14N) in its ground vibrational state.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Here, the electric quadrupole interaction is due to the 14N-nucleus, the hyperfine nuclear spin-spin splitting is from the magnetic coupling between nitrogen, 14N (*I*N = 1), and hydrogen, 1H (*I*H = 1⁄2), and a hydrogen spin-rotation interaction due to the 1H-nucleus.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] These contributing interactions to the hyperfine structure in the molecule are listed here in descending order of influence.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Sub-doppler techniques have been used to discern the hyperfine structure in HCN rotational transitions.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The dipole selection rules for HCN hyperfine structure transitions are $\Delta J=1$ , $\Delta F=\{0,\pm 1\}$ , where J is the rotational quantum number and F is the total rotational quantum number inclusive of nuclear spin ( $F=J+I_{\text{N}}$ ), respectively.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The lowest transition ( $J=1\rightarrow 0$ ) splits into a hyperfine triplet.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Using the selection rules, the hyperfine pattern of $J=2\rightarrow 1$ transition and higher dipole transitions is in the form of a hyperfine sextet.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] However, one of these components ( $\Delta F=-1$ ) carries only 0.6% of the rotational transition intensity in the case of $J=2\rightarrow 1$ .
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] This contribution drops for increasing J.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Each of these outliers carry ~ ${\tfrac {1}{2}}J^{2}$ (J is the upper rotational quantum number of the allowed dipole transition) the intensity of the entire transition.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] For consecutively higher-J transitions, there are small but significant changes in the relative intensities and positions of each individual hyperfine component.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Hyperfine interactions can be measured, among other ways, in atomic and molecular spectra, and in electron paramagnetic resonance spectra of free radicals and transition-metal ions.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] As the hyperfine splitting is very small, the transition frequencies are usually not located in the optical, but are in the range of radio- or microwave (also called sub-millimeter) frequencies.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Hyperfine structure gives the 21 cm line observed in H I regions in interstellar medium.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Carl Sagan and Frank Drake considered the hyperfine transition of hydrogen to be a sufficiently universal phenomenon so as to be used as a base unit of time and length on the Pioneer plaque and later Voyager Golden Record.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In submillimeter astronomy, heterodyne receivers are widely used in detecting electromagnetic signals from celestial objects such as star-forming core or young stellar objects.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The separations among neighboring components in a hyperfine spectrum of an observed rotational transition are usually small enough to fit within the receiver's IF band.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Since the optical depth varies with frequency, strength ratios among the hyperfine components differ from that of their intrinsic (or *optically thin*) intensities (these are so-called *hyperfine anomalies*, often observed in the rotational transitions of HCN).
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Thus, a more accurate determination of the optical depth is possible.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] From this, the object's physical parameters may be derived.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In nuclear spectroscopy methods, the nucleus is used to probe the local structure in materials.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The methods mainly base on hyperfine interactions with the surrounding atoms and ions.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Important methods are nuclear magnetic resonance, Mössbauer spectroscopy, perturbed angular correlation, and high-resolution inelastic neutron scattering.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The atomic vapor laser isotope separation (AVLIS) process uses the hyperfine splitting between optical transitions in uranium-235 and uranium-238 to selectively photo-ionize only the uranium-235 atoms and then separate the ionized particles from the non-ionized ones.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Precisely tuned dye lasers are used as the sources of the necessary exact wavelength radiation.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The hyperfine structure transition can be used to make a microwave notch filter with very high stability, repeatability, and Q factor, which can thus be used as a basis for very precise atomic clocks.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The term *transition frequency* denotes the frequency of radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the atom, and is equal to *f* = Δ*E*/*h*, where Δ*E* is difference in energy between the levels and *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Typically, the transition frequency of a particular isotope of caesium or rubidium atoms is used as a basis for these clocks.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Due to the accuracy of hyperfine structure transition-based atomic clocks, they are now used as the basis for the definition of the second.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] One second is now *defined* to be exactly 9192631770 cycles of the hyperfine structure transition frequency of caesium-133 atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] On October 21, 1983, the 17th CGPM defined the meter as the length of the path travelled by light in a vacuum during a time interval of ⁠1/299,792,458⁠ of a second.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The hyperfine splitting in hydrogen and in muonium have been used to measure the value of the fine-structure constant α.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Comparison with measurements of α in other physical systems provides a stringent test of QED.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The hyperfine states of a trapped ion are commonly used for storing qubits in ion-trap quantum computing.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] They have the advantage of having very long lifetimes, experimentally exceeding ~10 minutes (compared to ~1 s for metastable electronic levels).
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] The frequency associated with the states' energy separation is in the microwave region, making it possible to drive hyperfine transitions using microwave radiation.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] However, at present no emitter is available that can be focused to address a particular ion from a sequence.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] Instead, a pair of laser pulses can be used to drive the transition, by having their frequency difference (*detuning*) equal to the required transition's frequency.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] This is essentially a stimulated Raman transition.
[src:atomic-physics/hyperfine-structure] In addition, near-field gradients have been exploited to individually address two ions separated by approximately 4.3 micrometers directly with microwave radiation.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] In atomic physics, the **Rydberg formula** calculates the wavelengths of a spectral line in many chemical elements.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The formula was primarily presented as a generalization of the Balmer series for all atomic electron transitions of hydrogen.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] It was first empirically stated in 1888 by the Swedish physicist Johannes Rydberg, then theoretically by Niels Bohr in 1913, who used a primitive form of quantum mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The formula directly generalizes the equations used to calculate the wavelengths of the hydrogen spectral series.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] In 1890, Rydberg proposed on a formula describing the relation between the wavelengths in spectral lines of alkali metals.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] He noticed that lines came in series and he found that he could simplify his calculations by specifying the lines in terms of their wavenumber (the number of waves occupying the unit length, equal to 1/*λ*, the inverse of the wavelength) rather than their wavelength.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] He plotted the wavenumbers (*n*) of successive lines in each series against consecutive integers which represented the order of the lines in that particular series.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Finding that the resulting curves were similarly shaped, he sought a single function which could generate all of them, when appropriate constants were inserted.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] First he tried the formula: $\textstyle n=n_{0}-{\frac {C_{0}}{m+m'}}$ , where *n* is the line's wavenumber, *n*0 is the series limit, *m* is the line's ordinal number in the series, *m*′ is a constant different for different series and *C*0 is a universal constant.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Rydberg therefore rewrote Balmer's formula in terms of wavenumbers, as $\textstyle n=n_{0}-{4n_{0} \over m^{2}}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The term ${\text{C}}_{0}$ was found to be a universal constant common to all elements, equal to 4/*h*.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] This constant is now known as the Rydberg constant, and *m*′ is known as the quantum defect.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] As stressed by Niels Bohr, expressing results in terms of wavenumber, not wavelength, was the key to Rydberg's discovery.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The fundamental role of wavenumbers was also emphasized by the Rydberg-Ritz combination principle of 1908.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The fundamental reason for this lies in quantum mechanics.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Light's wavenumber is proportional to frequency $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\lambda }}={\frac {f}{c}}$ , and therefore also proportional to light's quantum energy *E*.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Thus, $\textstyle {\frac {1}{\lambda }}={\frac {E}{hc}}$ (in this formula the *h* represents the Planck constant).
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Modern and legitimate understanding is that Rydberg's findings were a reflection of the underlying simplicity of the behavior of spectral lines, in terms of fixed (quantized) *energy* differences between electron orbitals in atoms.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Rydberg's 1888 classical expression for the form of the spectral series was not accompanied by a physical explanation.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Thus he has been able to compute the value of Rydberg's heuristic constant $N_{0}$ from his atom theory and set the integers $\mu _{1}$ and $\mu _{2}$ to zero.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The effect is to predict new series corresponding to $\tau _{2}=1$ in the extreme ultraviolet unknown to Rydberg.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] In Bohr's conception of the atom, the integer Rydberg (and Balmer) *n* numbers represent electron orbitals at different integral distances from the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] A frequency (or spectral energy) emitted in a transition from *n*1 to *n*2 therefore represents the photon energy emitted or absorbed when an electron makes a jump from orbital 1 to orbital 2.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Later models found that the values for *n*1 and *n*2 corresponded to the principal quantum numbers of the two orbitals.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The Rydberg formula can be interpreted both through the semi-classical Bohr model and through fully quantum-mechanical treatments of the hydrogen atom.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] In the Bohr model, electrons occupy quantized orbits whose energies vary.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] When an electron transitions from a higher level to a lower level a photon is emitted with a wavelength matching the Rydberg expression.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Modern quantum mechanics arrives at the same result from the Schrödinger equation for an electron bound by a Coulomb potential.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Differences in the energy eigenvalues of the hydrogen atom reproduce the observed Rydberg dependence, while relativistic and spin corrections appear when the Dirac equation, fine-structure interactions, and quantum electrodynamics (QED) effects are included.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] These refinements explain small deviations from the simple formula, such as the Lamb shift and hyperfine splittings in hydrogen-like systems.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] By setting $n_{1}$ to 1 and letting $n_{2}$ run from 2 to infinity, the spectral lines known as the Lyman series converging to 91 nm are obtained.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Other named series correspond to increasingly higher values of $n_{1}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] This formula can be directly applied only to hydrogen-like, also called *hydrogenic* atoms of chemical elements, i.e. atoms with only one electron being affected by an effective nuclear charge (which is easily estimated).
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Examples would include He+, Li2+, Be3+ etc., where no other electrons exist in the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] This is analogous to the Lyman-alpha line transition for hydrogen, and has the same frequency factor.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Because the 2p electron is not screened by any other electrons in the atom from the nucleus, the nuclear charge is diminished only by the single remaining 1s electron, causing the system to be effectively a hydrogenic atom, but with a diminished nuclear charge *Z* − 1.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Its frequency is thus the Lyman-alpha hydrogen frequency, increased by a factor of (*Z* − 1)2.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] See the biography of Henry Moseley for the historical importance of this law, which was derived empirically at about the same time it was explained by the Bohr model of the atom.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] For other spectral transitions in multi-electron atoms, the Rydberg formula generally provides *incorrect* results, since the magnitude of the screening of inner electrons for outer-electron transitions is variable and cannot be compensated for in the simple manner above.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The correction to the Rydberg formula for these atoms is known as the quantum defect.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] The classical Rydberg formula assumes an infinitely massive nucleus; however, in real atoms the nucleus has finite mass.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] In the Bohr model the electron and nucleus should orbit their mutual center of mass.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] In quantum mechanical calculations this leads to the introduction of a reduced mass, producing a slightly modified Rydberg constant that varies depending on the isotope.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] Additional corrections arise from relativistic motion of the electron, vacuum polarization, self-energy contributions, and other QED effects, all of which are essential in high-precision spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-physics/rydberg-formula] These corrections become especially important for high-Z hydrogen-like ions, where relativistic velocities and strong Coulomb fields generate observable deviations from the nonrelativistic prediction.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The **Zeeman effect** (Dutch: [ˈzeːmɑn]) is the splitting of a spectral line into several components in the presence of a static magnetic field.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] It is caused by the interaction of the magnetic field with the magnetic moments of the atomic electrons associated with their orbital motion and spin; this interaction shifts some orbital energies more than others, resulting in the split spectrum.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The effect is named after the Dutch physicist Pieter Zeeman, who discovered it in 1896 and received the Nobel Prize in Physics for it in 1902.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] It is analogous to the Stark effect, the splitting of a spectral line into several components in the presence of an electric field.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Also, similar to the Stark effect, transitions between different components have, in general, different intensities, with some being entirely forbidden (in the dipole approximation), as governed by the selection rules.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Since the distance between the Zeeman sub-levels is a function of magnetic field strength, this effect can be used to measure magnetic field strength, e.g. that of the Sun and other stars or in laboratory plasmas.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In 1896, Zeeman learned that his laboratory had one of Henry Augustus Rowland's highest resolving diffraction gratings.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Zeeman had read James Clerk Maxwell's article in *Encyclopædia Britannica* describing Michael Faraday's failed attempts to influence light with magnetism.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Zeeman wondered if the new spectrographic techniques could succeed where early efforts had not.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When illuminated by a slit-shaped source, the grating produces a long array of slit images corresponding to different wavelengths.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Zeeman placed a piece of asbestos soaked in salt water into a Bunsen burner flame at the source of the grating: he could easily see two lines in the sodium light emission spectrum.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Switching on a strong (about one tesla) electromagnet around the flame, he observed a slight broadening of the lines.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When Zeeman switched to cadmium as the source, he observed the spectral lines split when the magnetic field was applied.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] These splittings could be analyzed with Hendrik Lorentz's then-new electron theory.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] It is now known that the magnetic effects on sodium require quantum-mechanical treatment.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Zeeman and Lorentz were awarded the 1902 Nobel Prize; in his acceptance speech Zeeman explained his apparatus and showed slides of the spectrographic images.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Historically, one distinguishes between the **normal** and an **anomalous Zeeman effect** (discovered by Thomas Preston in Dublin, Ireland).
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The anomalous effect appears on transitions where the net spin of the electrons is non-zero.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] It was called "anomalous" because the electron spin had not yet been discovered, and so there was no good explanation for it at the time that Zeeman observed the effect.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] At higher magnetic field strength the effect ceases to be linear.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] At even higher field strengths, comparable to the strength of the atom's internal field, the electron coupling is disturbed and the spectral lines rearrange.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This is called the **Paschen–Back effect**.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In modern scientific literature, these terms are rarely used, with a tendency to use just the "Zeeman effect".
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Another rarely used obscure term is **inverse Zeeman effect**, referring to the Zeeman effect in an absorption spectral line.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] A similar effect, splitting of the nuclear energy levels in the presence of a magnetic field, is referred to as the **nuclear Zeeman effect**.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The magnetic moment consists of the electronic and nuclear parts; however, the latter is many orders of magnitude smaller and will be neglected here.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Therefore, ${\vec {\mu }}\approx -{\frac {\mu _{\text{B}}g{\vec {J}}}{\hbar }},$ where $\mu _{\text{B}}$ is the Bohr magneton, ${\vec {J}}$ is the total electronic angular momentum, and g is the Landé g-factor.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] If the interaction term $V_{\text{M}}$ is small (less than the fine structure), it can be treated as a perturbation; this is the Zeeman effect proper.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In the Paschen–Back effect, described below, $V_{\text{M}}$ exceeds the LS coupling significantly (but is still small compared to $H_{0}$ ).
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In ultra-strong magnetic fields, the magnetic-field interaction may exceed $H_{0}$ , in which case the atom can no longer exist in its normal meaning, and one talks about Landau levels instead.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] There are intermediate cases that are more complex than these limit cases.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] If the spin–orbit interaction dominates over the effect of the external magnetic field, ${\vec {L}}$ and ${\vec {S}}$ are not separately conserved, only the total angular momentum ${\vec {J}}={\vec {L}}+{\vec {S}}$ is.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The spin and orbital angular momentum vectors can be thought of as precessing about the (fixed) total angular momentum vector ${\vec {J}}$ .
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Note in particular that the size of the energy splitting is different for the different orbitals because the *gJ* values are different.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Fine-structure splitting occurs even in the absence of a magnetic field, as it is due to spin–orbit coupling.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Depicted on the right is the additional Zeeman splitting, which occurs in the presence of magnetic fields.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The Paschen–Back effect is the splitting of atomic energy levels in the presence of a strong magnetic field.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This occurs when an external magnetic field is sufficiently strong to disrupt the coupling between orbital ( ${\vec {L}}$ ) and spin ( ${\vec {S}}$ ) angular momenta.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This effect is the strong-field limit of the Zeeman effect.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When $s=0$ , the two effects are equivalent.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The effect was named after the German physicists Friedrich Paschen and Ernst E.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When the magnetic-field perturbation significantly exceeds the spin–orbit interaction, one can safely assume $[H_{0},S]=0$ .
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This allows the expectation values of $L_{z}$ and $S_{z}$ to be easily evaluated for a state $|\psi \rangle$ .
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The above may be read as implying that the LS-coupling is completely broken by the external field.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] However, $m_{l}$ and $m_{s}$ are still "good" quantum numbers.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Together with the selection rules for an electric dipole transition, i.e., $\Delta s=0,\Delta m_{s}=0,\Delta l=\pm 1,\Delta m_{l}=0,\pm 1$ this allows to ignore the spin degree of freedom altogether.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] As a result, only three spectral lines will be visible, corresponding to the $\Delta m_{l}=0,\pm 1$ selection rule.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The splitting $\Delta E=B\mu _{\rm {B}}\Delta m_{l}$ is *independent* of the unperturbed energies and electronic configurations of the levels being considered.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] More precisely, if $s\neq 0$ , each of these three components is actually a group of several transitions due to the residual spin–orbit coupling and relativistic corrections (which are of the same order, known as 'fine structure').
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In this example, the fine-structure corrections are ignored.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In the case of weak magnetic fields, the Zeeman interaction can be treated as a perturbation to the $|F,m_{f}\rangle$ basis.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] In the high field regime, the magnetic field becomes so strong that the Zeeman effect will dominate, and one must use a more complete basis of $|I,J,m_{I},m_{J}\rangle$ or just $|m_{I},m_{J}\rangle$ since I and J will be constant within a given level.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] To get the complete picture, including intermediate field strengths, we must consider eigenstates which are superpositions of the $|F,m_{F}\rangle$ and $|m_{I},m_{J}\rangle$ basis states.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] For $J=1/2$ , the Hamiltonian can be solved analytically, resulting in the **Breit–Rabi formula** (named after Gregory Breit and Isidor Isaac Rabi).
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Notably, the electric quadrupole interaction is zero for $L=0$ ( $J=1/2$ ), so this formula is fairly accurate.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] as long as $m_{L}$ lies in the range ${-L,\dots ...,L}$ (otherwise, they return zero).
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] We can now see that at all times, the total angular momentum projection $m_{F}=m_{J}+m_{I}$ will be conserved.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This is because both $J_{z}$ and $I_{z}$ leave states with definite $m_{J}$ and $m_{I}$ unchanged, while $J_{+}I_{-}$ and $J_{-}I_{+}$ either increase $m_{J}$ and decrease $m_{I}$ or vice versa, so the sum is always unaffected.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Furthermore, since $J=1/2$ there are only two possible values of $m_{J}$ which are $\pm 1/2$ .
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This pair of states is a two-level quantum mechanical system.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This equation is known as the **Breit–Rabi formula** and is useful for systems with one valence electron in an s ( $J=1/2$ ) level.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Note that index F in $\Delta E_{F=I\pm 1/2}$ should be considered not as total angular momentum of the atom but as *asymptotic total angular momentum*.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] It is equal to total angular momentum only if $B=0$ otherwise eigenvectors corresponding different eigenvalues of the Hamiltonian are the superpositions of states with different F but equal $m_{F}$ (the only exceptions are $|F=I+1/2,m_{F}=\pm F\rangle$ ).
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] George Ellery Hale was the first to notice the Zeeman effect in the solar spectra, indicating the existence of strong magnetic fields in sunspots.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Such fields can be quite high, on the order of 0.1 tesla or higher.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Today, the Zeeman effect is used to produce magnetograms showing the variation of magnetic field on the Sun, and to analyze the magnetic field geometries in other stars.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The Zeeman effect is utilized in many laser cooling applications such as a magneto-optical trap and the Zeeman slower.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Zeeman-energy mediated coupling of spin and orbital motions is used in spintronics for controlling electron spins in quantum dots through electric dipole spin resonance.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Old high-precision frequency standards, i.e. hyperfine structure transition-based atomic clocks, may require periodic fine-tuning due to exposure to magnetic fields.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This is carried out by measuring the Zeeman effect on specific hyperfine structure transition levels of the source element (cesium) and applying a uniformly precise, low-strength magnetic field to said source, in a process known as degaussing.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The Zeeman effect may also be utilized to improve accuracy in atomic absorption spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] A theory about the magnetic sense of birds assumes that a protein in the retina is changed due to the Zeeman effect.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The nuclear Zeeman effect is important in such applications as nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and Mössbauer spectroscopy.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The electron spin resonance spectroscopy is based on the Zeeman effect.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The Zeeman effect can be demonstrated by placing a sodium vapor source in a powerful electromagnet and viewing a sodium vapor lamp through the magnet opening (see diagram).
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] With magnet off, the sodium vapor source will block the lamp light; when the magnet is turned on the lamp light will be visible through the vapor.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The sodium vapor can be created by sealing sodium metal in an evacuated glass tube and heating it while the tube is in the magnet.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] Alternatively, salt (sodium chloride) on a ceramic stick can be placed in the flame of Bunsen burner as the sodium vapor source.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When the magnetic field is energized, the lamp image will be brighter.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] However, the magnetic field also affects the flame, making the observation depend upon more than just the Zeeman effect.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] These issues also plagued Zeeman's original work; he devoted considerable effort to ensure his observations were truly an effect of magnetism on light emission.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When salt is added to the Bunsen burner, it dissociates to give sodium and chloride.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The sodium atoms get excited due to photons from the sodium vapour lamp, with electrons excited from 3s to 3p states, absorbing light in the process.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] The sodium vapour lamp emits light at 589nm, which has precisely the energy to excite an electron of a sodium atom.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] If it was an atom of another element, like chlorine, shadow will not be formed.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] When a magnetic field is applied, due to the Zeeman effect the spectral line of sodium gets split into several components.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] This means the energy difference between the 3s and 3p atomic orbitals will change.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] As the sodium vapour lamp don't precisely deliver the right frequency anymore, light doesn't get absorbed and passes through, resulting in the shadow dimming.
[src:atomic-physics/zeeman-effect] As the magnetic field strength is increased, the shift in the spectral lines increases and lamp light is transmitted.
